The girls at 13 are just more mature than boys of that age psychologically and developmentally.  Boys hit their growing spurt around 14-15.  So girls have two years in school that they might be faster or more talented in the strength/speed sports.  [Actually 4 years ago one of my boys played against a 12 year old girl in football that was laying kids out. They just don't have the physical attributes that will help them, unless they start altering their physical attributes.  I remember my college (large D1 school) having the WNBA players stay in the dorms over the summer.  I was on the basketball practice team.  Was probably at the level of a DIII starter but nothing great.  We would play the WNBA girls daily.  My team would include 1-2 guys from practice squade and 2-3 \"good\" pickup players. </p>\n\n<p>In their three weeks there the WNBA players never won a game.  They scratched, clawed, brought out their 6-7 big, it didn't matter.  They couldn't stop our first step or the power drive.   Number don't lie.  We won probably close to 100 games.  Most of these girls were stars at big D1 programs.  We didn't hold back at all (mainly because they started playing dirty in game one) but we weren't also \"great\" players.  I believe all of the girls we played were better basketball players than us - fundamentals, shooting, tactic, positioning, whatever - but the athletic disadvantage was too much to make up.</p>\n\n<p>What sport are women closest to catching men?  I would think it would be the marathon.  Running that distance requires using your body's existing fat reserves.  Women have an advantage here. 		"Body" : "<p>How about this? -> <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/4668656/magento-get-a-static-block-as-html-in-a-phtml-file\">https://stackoverflow.com/questions/4668656/magento-get-a-static-block-as-html-in-a-phtml-file</a></p>\n\n<p>Now you create the blocks in current layout and I'm not sure how they would act. Maybe you should try something like this (in your modules app/design/frontend/default/base/your_company/your_module.xml - or whatever xml file name you defined in config.xml):</p>\n\n<pre><code><layout>\n    <default> <!-- or your store / theme handle -->\n        <reference name=\"content\">\n            <block type=\"cms/block\" name=\"movie\" as=\"movie\">\n                <action method=\"setBlockId\">\n                    <block_id>movie</block_id>\n                </action>\n            </block>\n            <block type=\"cms/block\" name=\"music\" as=\"music\">\n                <action method=\"setBlockId\">\n                    <block_id>music</block_id>\n                </action>\n            </block>\n        </reference>\n    </default>\n</layout>\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>And then in your code:</p>\n\n<pre><code>$appliedFilters = Mage::getSingleton('catalog/layer')->getState()->getFilters();\nforeach ($appliedFilters as $item) {\n    if ($item->getFilter()->getRequestVar() == 'my_attribute1') {\n        echo $this->getChildHtml('movie');\n    }\n    else if ($item->getFilter()->getRequestVar() == 'my_attribute2') {\n        echo $this->getChildHtml('music');\n    }\n}\n</code></pre>",

		"Title" : "Initial Value Problem using Finite Element",
		"Body" : "<p>I am trying to implement a FEM solver for the following initial value problem\n\\begin{align}\n\\frac{\\partial u}{\\partial t} - \\nabla^2 u &= f\\quad \\text{ in } \\Omega\\times (0,T)\\\\\nu &= g\\quad \\text{ on }\\partial\\Omega\\times(0,T)\\\\\nu(x,y,0) &= u_0(x,y)\n\\end{align}\nwhere $\\Omega\\subset\\mathbb{R}^2$ is just a rectangular domain. The functions $f$ and $g$ can vary with time. I have discretized this IVP into\n$$\\mathbf{B}\\frac{\\partial}{\\partial t}\\mathbf{u} + \\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{u} = \\mathbf{l} $$\nwhere\n\\begin{align}\n\\text{B}_{ij} &= \\int_\\Omega \\phi_i\\phi_j\\\\\n\\text{A}_{ij} &= \\int_\\Omega \\nabla\\phi_i\\nabla\\phi_j\\\\\nl_i &= \\int_\\Omega \\phi_i f\n\\end{align}\nand I can assemble these matrices and vector. I have also discretized time to get the time-stepping scheme\n$$(\\mathbf{B}+k\\theta\\mathbf{A})\\mathbf{u}^{n+1} = (\\mathbf{B}-k(1-\\theta)\\mathbf{A})\\mathbf{u}^n + k(\\theta \\mathbf{l}^n + (1-\\theta)\\mathbf{l}^{n+1}), $$\nwhere $\\theta\\in[0,1]$ and $k$ is the time-step.</p>\n\n<p>Here comes my problem. How exactly do I impose the boundary and initial condition, implementation-wise? What changes should I make to the matrices $\\mathbf{A},\\mathbf{B}$, etc? Should I do anything at each time-step? I feel like it shouldn't be too hard, however when the time is introduced it suddenly confuses me.</p>\n\n<p>Thanks</p>",

		"Title" : "I wanted to add a blog post I wrote on this topic on my blog Dear Sports...",
		"Body" : "<p>I wanted to add a blog post I wrote on this topic on my blog Dear Sports Fan: <a href=\"http://wp.me/p1A2WF-ND\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://wp.me/p1A2WF-ND</a>.</p>\n\n<p>If you're in a tl/dr mood, I would just say that in order to define what a catch is, the NFL had to create some dividing line between not a catch and a catch. They chose to define it as a player who establishes control of the ball, lands on the field, and then holds it for long enough to do something else. This something else is commonly referred to as a football move. </p>\n\n<p>This seems like a reasonable enough line to draw because if a player has the time and wherewithal to do something else, he's probably done catching the ball. If he doesn't, he's probably still in the process of catching the ball.</p>\n\n<p>Thanks,\nEzra</p>",

		"Title" : "He was not asking about auto completion.  Although that is a problem in ...",
		"Body" : "<p>He was not asking about auto completion.  Although that is a problem in of itself.  The answers on this page solved neither problem for me.  He is referring to the execute command.  When you execute your code it doesn't always use the version of python described in the preferences or that you want for it to use.  Check the top of your .py file.  See where there is a shebang command</p>\n\n<pre><code>#!/usr/bin/python\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>change that to</p>\n\n<pre><code>#!/usr/bin/python3\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>or whatever path is the path to your interpreter of choice.</p>\n\n<p>if this doesn't exist, place it at the top of your .py file and I can almost fully guarantee that it will fix your problem.</p>\n\n<p>I hope this response comes not too late and that it can still help out the lost and confused somewhere out there.</p>\n\n<p>It solved the problem for me.  It took me a whole day of research and I finally figured this out by reading through the python manual at <a href=\"https://docs.python.org\" rel=\"nofollow\">https://docs.python.org</a></p>\n\n<p>Tons of great information in those documents, check em out!</p>\n\n<p>Please let me know if this solved your problem as well.</p>",

		"Title" : "I use Podcasts on my MacBook Pro, my iPhone 5 and my iPad Air 2. The onl...",
		"Body" : "<p>I use Podcasts on my MacBook Pro, my iPhone 5 and my iPad Air 2. The only thing that I have found to work is this setup.</p>\n\n<p>All my downloads of new episodes, etc. are done on the MacBook Pro. I basically leave iTunes running most of the time even when I am away and only have my portable devices with me.</p>\n\n<p>I use Playlists on the MacBook pro iTunes to sort episodes for which device. Video podcasts primarily go to the iPad and audio primarily to the phone, but when flying I often put audio podcasts on the iPad to save battery life on the phone.</p>\n\n<p>Then in iTunes I connect each device and use the settings for the device to control which podcasts and which playlists are synced to the device. I generally only sync checked files and I uncheck episodes after they are played.</p>\n\n<p>Also in iTunes on the MacBook Pro I have smart playlists for recently played and recently added and I use those to help me find the newer Podcast episodes quickly and to uncheck played episodes quickly.</p>\n\n<p>This is admittedly a lot of work. I spend a couple hours or more each week managing my playlists. I sync nearly every day to add new episodes and clean up old episodes. I just could never make the \"automatic\" sync'ing work the way I wanted, so I decided to take control of it with these techniques.</p>\n\n<p>Final Note: in iTunes Preferences on the Store tab, I turn off Sync Podcast subscriptions and settings. I have found there is a bug in this process that sometimes causes iTunes to stop downloading any podcasts. There was some discussion on the Apple Support Forums that pointed me to this change.</p>",

		"Title" : "I'll expand on Mark's and SRKX's answers which are both correct but brie...",
		"Body" : "<p>I'll expand on Mark's and SRKX's answers which are both correct but brief.  To be clear the words long and short have been generalized in finance.  They used to mean that you owned a stock or had sold a stock short.  Now they are often used to say you make money when a value goes up (long) or make money when some value goes down (short).</p>\n\n<p>In this case whenever you own a call or a put you are \"long\" volatility.  Meaning that as volatility increases the value of your position increases (holding everything else the same).  How much added value that you get for an certain increase in volatility (called vega) <a href=\"http://totaloptions.com.au/818/introduction-to-options-trading-option-vega/\" rel=\"nofollow\">depends on how in/out of the money the option is at currently</a> among other things, but if you own the call/put it is always positive as more volatility means more possible upside.</p>\n\n<p>When you sell calls or puts then volatility decreases are good for your position so you are called \"short\" vol.</p>",

		"Body" : "<p>I am currently dealing with the same thing, and have been for a while now. The comments are harsh judgements like you think the asker was given a parenting handbook and that the information provided here is something that only idiots and bad parents don't know. I hear child development and education backgrounds, maybe some psychology/behavioral health. YOU  should know this stuff, yes. Is it something that a normal run-of-the-mill parent should? No. Not unless they bury their face in books and can decide to agree with one of the many conflicting theories of \"good parenting\". </p>\n\n<p>Some of us have no \"good\" examples of how things are supposed to be done and are just trying to not make the same mistakes as our parents. The advice seems valid and well delivered but did it really have to be preceded by implicit scoffs and 'How could you be so stupid\"-like comments?</p>\n\n<p>Expectations are not set too high when you expect your child to do simple tasks without every day being an argument...for EVERY task.</p>\n\n<p>Well let me tell you. I have been dealing with my 10 y/o son not showing interest in ANYTHING and dragging butt about everything in his daily tasks. I have tried everything. I STARTED with explaining why it's important to brush teeth and take a good shower everyday. I asked the exact preferences that were listed here:</p>\n\n<p>\"Do you want to shower at night or in the morning?\" \n\"Do you want to brush your teeth before or after breakfast?\" \n\"Do you want to play for a little while before you start homework?\" \n\"How about after a snack?\"\n\"Do you want to do your homework at the breakfast bar or table?\" \n\"Do you think it would be easier to stay focused or more comfortable if you had a desk in your room? Let's try and see.\" </p>\n\n<p>I have provided encouragement, enforced consequences, provided positive reinforcement, and taken things away. We have time-outs for when either of us get frustrated and we both go to our own spaces to reflect and regroup. I have tried a LOT of different ways to skin this cat. What works for some does not ALWAYS work ALL of the time. I find that as soon as I find something that seems like it is working, it just doesn't and I have to change methods. That has been going on since he was 2 or 3. </p>\n\n<p>I also have an 11 y/o daughter. I have used the same parenting style with her from the beginning. She is autonomous, successful in anything she tries, and interested in everything. She is smart, has great friends, and has great confidence. Different cat.</p>\n\n<p>The problem with some of the comments is that they seem abrasive and sound condescending. Why not ask questions like:\n \"What kind of encouragement have you tried?\"\n\"Which tasks are the most difficult?\"\n\"Have you sat him down when not trying to get him to do something and just asked how he feels about each thing? Why does he think or feel like he does about fulfilling his responsibilities?\" \n\"There have been no \"diagnoses\" in the family but have you considered taking him to speak with someone anyway?\" </p>\n\n<p>Talking to someone that is trained to communicate with children can be helpful. Sometimes it is just an issue of parents not knowing how to communicate with their child. I am still trying to figure it out myself. Kids can be 10 different people by the time they reach double digits. </p>\n\n<p>I say (a couple of years too late) good job for caring enough to seek guidance. We don't have all of the answers and sometimes it takes the wisdom of the village to survive the parent-child relationship. That being said, the villager should be able to ask for the wisdom without feeling attacked. I understand that the asker may have not read the responses that way but I did. So may others that stumble upon this post. All I typed in the search engine was \"how to help my child find interests\". </p>\n\n<p>How about trying to build up or encourage the parent? Do we not still need it? Or, is it a good idea to criticize someone that may already be feeling less-than great about how they're doing in one of life's most challenging tasks? People don't grow out of needing support.</p>\n\n<p>By the way, my son has outgrown the fighting me on things. Most of the time he just complains and whines about everything or will do bare minimum at best without me staying on him. </p>\n\n<p>One thing to help with brushing teeth that parents can try is using the pre-rinse that stains the \"yuk\" on teeth so they see how they're doing. The first time they get it all off before you check is self-rewarding for them. Also, the timed electric toothbrushes help them realize how long it really takes. We use the Sonicare for kids by Phillips. It beeps every 30 seconds letting them know when to switch sections. They can pause it to spit and you can hear it go throught the cycle without having to watch them like a hawk. The vibration tickles for a few days but they get used to it. Another good thing about it is that if they don't put a lot of physical work into it, the toothbrush still gets the job done as long as they actually move it to each part. I'm not endorsing that specific brand, I just don't have knowledge of other brands' features. It is definitely more expensive than regular toothbrushes but for me, worth it in what I save at the dentist. Huge improvement in dental health after the switch.</p>",

//was verified against matlab\nSamples = applyFilter(Samples,getWindow(iSizeFFT,sWindow));\n</code></pre>\n\n<p><strong>Trying to Normalize</strong></p>\n\n<p>Get the Log10 of of absolute value of each complex item of array of FFT, later multiply by 20</p>\n\n<pre><code>//fft:  Returns a complex array with FFT (the result was tested and it is equal to Matlab)\n//getArrayComplexMod: Returns a double array with absolute value of each complex number\n//getRealArrayLog10: Returns a double array with Math.log of each double element\n//getRealArrayScalarMult: Returns a double array multiplying each double element with 20.0\n\nSamples = getRealArrayScalarMult(getRealArrayLog10(getArrayComplexMod(fft(Samples))),20.0);\n</code></pre>\n\n<p><strong>Obtain the Frequency in Hertz</strong></p>\n\n<pre><code>//Now the freq or bins\ndouble[] bins = new double[iSizeFFT]; i < dSamples.length; i++) {\n      filteredSamples[i - PosSample] = 0;\n      for (int j = 0; j < dFilter.length; j++) {\n        if(!((i - j) < 0)) {\n          filteredSamples[i - PosSample] += dSamples[i-j]*dFilter[j];\n        }\n      }\n    }\n    return filteredSamples;\n  }\n</code></pre>",

	{
		"ReportLink" : "http://chat.meta.stackexchange.com/transcript/message/2945874",
		"PostUrl" : "http://physics.stackexchange.com/a/153486",
		"Site" : "physics.stackexchange.com",
		"Title" : "Briefly, no.\n\nCharged particle interaction is fundamentally a non-instan...",
		"Body" : "<p>Briefly, no.</p>\n\n<p>Charged particle interaction is fundamentally a non-instantaneous photon exchange. The interaction can be written or expanded as the ''naive'' instantaneous interaction ($e^2/r$) plus a photon exchange portion which contains exactly a $-e^2/r$ term and a non-instantaneous (retarded in time) term. The author calls the first term the Coulomb interaction, and he calls the second the photon interaction. (We note that the sum of these two results in the cancelling of the instantaneous $e^2/r$ term, giving us a time-dependent expression for charged particle interaction, as expected.)</p>\n\n<p>Then I think the author says that since distances are small, times are also small, and so the instantaneous Coulomb term dominates. Thus it is acceptable in most cases to use the naive 19th century Coulomb definition.</p>\n\n<hr>\n\n<p><strong>Edit2</strong>:</p>\n\n<p>I agree that the author is being very semantically confusing, and even contradictory.</p>\n\n<p>The author is using a loose definition of the word \"interaction\" (as was I, before this edit).\nStrictly speaking, the expression \"$e^2/r$\" does not describe an interaction, but rather just tells us the strength of the force. That is, it doesn't say at all <em>how</em> the force arises, it just describes the end result. (Note the analogy to Newtonian vs Einsteinian gravity.)</p>\n\n<p>Thus you would call it the Coulomb Law; \"Coulomb Interaction\" is something that does not exist, or has not yet been proposed (since it would be an instantaneous action-at-a-distance mechanism). As far as we know, all charged particle interaction takes place by exchanging photons. (You could call the exchange of photons the \"Coulomb Interaction\", but then there wouldn't be the distinction that the author makes.)</p>\n\n<p>The author is essentially trying to say that we can ignore the mechanism by which the charged particles interact, and study only the resultant forces and effects arising from their interaction.\nIt would be acceptable, in my opinion, to ignore that somewhat misleading paragraph of the text.</p>",

		"Title" : "How about just to remember pointer when touching down and check that on ...",
		"Body" : "<p>How about just to remember pointer when touching down and check that on touch up instead of coordinates? Something like this:</p>\n\n<pre><code>private int jumpPointer;\n\n@Override\npublic boolean touchDown(int x, int y, int pointer, int button) {\n    if((x > (5*width)/7 && y < (2*height)/7)) {\n        controller.jumpPressed(); //make the character jump\n        jumpPointer = pointer;\n    }\n    return false;\n}\n\n@Override\npublic boolean touchUp(int x, int y, int pointer, int button) {\n    if (pointer == jumpPointer && Gdx.app.getType().equals(ApplicationType.Android))\n        controller.jumpReleased();\n    }\n    return false;\n}\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Well, pointer is a bit oddly named in my opinion.  TouchIndex would probably have made more sense, especially with pointer having a pair of very well defined meanings already.  The pointer value is value between 0 and n (defined as 20 in LibGDX, in reality much lower) that represents the ORDER in which the touch event occurred in the event of multiple simultaneous touches.  Therefore if you have multiple fingers touching, a pointer value of 0 would indicate that this touch event represents the first finger to touch the screen, while a value of 3 would be the fourth finger to touch the screen.</p>",

		"Title" : "reduction of maxcut problem",
		"Body" : "<p>Show that if the MAX CUT decision problem can be solved in polynomial time so can the MAX CUT optimization problem by writing an algorithm that solves the optimization problem using an algorithm for the decision problem as a subroutine</p>\n\n<p>MAX CUT</p>\n\n<p>INSTANCE: A graph G = (V,E), a function c giving each edge e \u2208 E an integer capacity c(e) and an integer B. QUESTION: (D) Does the graph have a cut of size at least B? (O) Find a cut with the maximum size.</p>\n\n<pre><code>Algorithm\n\nFind the maxcut value k by binary search from 1 to m using decision subroutine\n     where m is global maximum value\nfor all edge e \u2208 E\n  select a edge e=(u,v) \u2208 E, construct G' after removing egde e from G\n  if SUBROUTINE(G',k)=1 =>removal of edge has no effect on MAXCUT\n    add u and v to same set S or S'(use 2 SAT to determine which group)\n  else\n    add u and v to different sets S or S'\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>This algorithm works only if there is only one MAXCUT solution in the graph(i have considered only unweighted graph). In case of a complete graph this algorithm fails as there is more than one MAXCUT solution present.</p>\n\n<p>consider 4 nodes complete graph with edges (1,2),(1,3),(1,4),(2,3),(2,4),(3,4). The algorithm fails because when we remove any one edge still there is a MAXCUT of size 4.</p>\n\n<p>Please suggest any other algorithm which works or any additional condition which can solve this problem.</p>\n\n<p>Thanks in advance</p>",

	{
		"ReportLink" : "http://chat.meta.stackexchange.com/transcript/message/2942751",
		"PostUrl" : "http://security.stackexchange.com/a/79813",
		"Site" : "security.stackexchange.com",
		"Title" : "Like others have said, firewall, and if you feel it necessary IDS/IPS to...",
		"Body" : "<p>Like others have said, firewall, and if you feel it necessary IDS/IPS too.  But to me, it's the wrong question.  You need to address these things:</p>\n\n<h2>Forensics</h2>\n\n<p>Have you managed to work out how you were comprimised before?  If not, it would be a good place to start.  Knowing how your system ended up with a RAT on it in the first place means you can close off that door</p>\n\n<h2>Firewall</h2>\n\n<p>As mentioned by a few others, firewall that stuff.  A box running two NICs and using   <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Uncomplicated_Firewall\" rel=\"nofollow\">UFW</a> or <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Iptables\" rel=\"nofollow\">Iptables</a> to filter traffic is a good start, although make sure that box is itself very locked down.  Consider whether you need to run each service on the firewall box too.  e.g. if it's in the same room as you, does it need SSH/telnet running, or can you just use it in person?</p>\n\n<h2>IDS/IPS</h2>\n\n<p>If you consider it necessary, you could even add an Intrusion Protection/Detection System to the box.  There are <a href=\"https://www.alienvault.com/blogs/security-essentials/open-source-intrusion-detection-tools-a-quick-overview\" rel=\"nofollow\">several freeware tools</a> to consider in this regard.</p>\n\n<h2>System hardening</h2>\n\n<p>Both on the box you proxy through, and the box you develop on, consider some hardening.  Get a software firewall that is good for your OS, and antivirus for that OS too, and ideally some way to check regularly for Rootkits etc.</p>\n\n<h2>Good practices</h2>\n\n<p>More important than any of the above is to adopt good practices.  It's no good setting up a hardware firewall if you then open ports whenever something doesn't work, and forget to address whether they need to stay open, and it's no good installing a rootkit finder if you never run it.</p>\n\n<p>All of this said, base what you do on a risk assessment (useful to know how previous exploits worked for risk assessment, too), and don't go overboard.  You could spend a week building a nice little setup with custom hardware firewalls, IDS/IPS protection, hardware level AV, and all manner of other stuff, but if you'd do better with a simpler set up and spending that time working, consider whether that's a better idea.</p>\n\n<h2>Audit</h2>\n\n<p>Try and find a decent security audit tool for your system.  If you are running linux, I find <a href=\"http://www.nongnu.org/tiger/\" rel=\"nofollow\">tiger</a> is pretty good, </p>\n\n<h2>Opportunism</h2>\n\n<p>The likelihood is that you weren't targeted.  Statistically speaking, people trying to make money out of security holes in a criminal way (like holding code to ransom) aren't seeking out particular individuals to exploit, but rather people who fit a certain demographic.  It's more likely that you were exploited last time because some script kiddie could find a dev server of some sort running or something like that, and was scanning for these particular things in order to perform the exploit on you that they did.  Your biggest aim is to make yourself hard to find and then target, as this is a much more likely scenario than a direct target of you and only you.  The other thing that makes me think this is that you were extorted for money, whereas a targetted attack would probably be trying to steal your code and keep it.</p>\n\n<p>Consider whether you may have been targeted, but I think on the whole, closing any security holes you can find will be a good first step.  I think you can probably avoid this problem again with just the firewall, but a lot depends on how you were comprimised.</p>",

		"PostUrl" : "http://german.stackexchange.com/a/20319",
		"Site" : "german.stackexchange.com",
		"Title" : "Wow, this one is hard.\nA very good idea is distinguishing between topics...",
		"Body" : "<p>Wow, this one is hard.<br>\nA very good idea is distinguishing between topics and people (like Kilian did). Maybe some more examples will help.</p>\n\n<p>You usually talk <em>about</em> a topic and generalize it to some point. The German \"\u00FCber\" does the same just like in \"\u00DCbersicht\". You ask somebody to tell you <em>about</em> something to get an impression. When I tell you something <em>about</em> a topic I am giving you more like a summary so you get the idea.</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>What is he talking about?. - \u00DCber was spricht er?<br>\n  (<em>He is talking about nature (in general)</em>).</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>When I talk <em>of</em> a certain topic I (maybe) want to convince/win you. I think the contents are more important here.</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>He is talking of nature and it's different animals. - Er redet von der Natur und den verschiednen Tieren.<br>\n  (Ending the sentence after \"nature\" in both languages feels odd because you expect something else to follow. At least I do.)</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p><br>To sum up:</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Did he tell you <strong>about</strong> something? - is generally asking (\u00FCber).<br>\n  Did you hear <strong>of</strong> this thing? - is going further into detail (von).</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>Some special case might be:</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Someone is talking well <strong>of</strong> you. (von, detail: talking <em>well</em>)<br>\n  Someone is talking <strong>about</strong> you (\u00FCber, in general, no judging)</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>Speaking of \"of\" and \"about\", I'm about to go off (so much confusion :D)</p>",

		"Body" : "<p>First of all, just flagging that you should call <code>require('modernizr')</code> instead of <code>require('modernizer')</code>.</p>\n\n<p>Secondly, to answer your question <em>\u201CIs there a way to use Modernizer from pack to include it modules without using this directive on page?</em></p>\n\n<p>Yes there is. It's the <a href=\"https://github.com/webpack/script-loader\" rel=\"nofollow\"><code>script-loader</code></a>. It basically allows you to require a library, and execute it as if it were inside a <code><script></code> tag. You'd use it by calling:</p>\n\n<pre><code>require('script-loader');\nrequire(script!modernizr);\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Remember to install <code>script-loader</code> in advance, by calling <code>npm install script-loader --save</code> in your command line.</p>",

		"Title" : "Figured out how to do it, still I think that it's not the best way to do...",
		"Body" : "<p>Figured out how to do it, still I think that it's not the best way to do it but it works and since the inputFields are rendered as select picklists in html and they all need the same style I added the following code in the style:</p>\n\n<pre><code>select {\n    height:33px;\n    width:255px;\n    font-size:14px;\n    font-style:italic;\n    font-weight:bold;\n    color:#26523C;\n    background-color:#9FA074; \n    text-align:left;\n    padding-top:7px;\n    padding-bottom:7px;\n    padding-left:10px;\n    border: 0;\n}\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>And added a div with the position where it should be rendered:</p>\n\n<pre><code><!-- Children picklist -->\n<div style=\"left:400px; top:275px;\">\n    <apex:inputField id=\"children\" value=\"{!Object__c.children__c}\"/>\n</div>\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>This way the dependent and controller picklists are rendered with same style as I wish it to be.</p>\n\n<p>@Uwe Heim: Thanks anyway, firebug's awesome and helped me out on this.</p>",

We cannot just return true without using f.submit, because then the task is not set\n        return false;\n    } else {\n        var msg = '<?php echo addslashes( JText::_('COM_VIRTUEMART_USER_FORM_MISSING_REQUIRED_JS') ); 		"Title" : "Dependencies are not restricted to verbs and their dependents. Attributi...",
		"Body" : "<p>Dependencies are not restricted to verbs and their dependents. Attributive adjectives, such as <strong>white</strong> in <em>white horses</em>, depend on their nouns. Hence <strong>holy</strong> should depend on <strong>shit</strong>. Since this is a modifying relationship (the adjective modifies the noun), the <em>Stanford Dependencies</em> take this to be a <strong>nmod</strong> (noun modification) dependency. (<a href=\"http://www.ling.ohio-state.edu/~mcdm/publications.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">The first paper</a> from the top lists common dependencies on the second page).</p>",

	{
		"ReportLink" : "http://chat.meta.stackexchange.com/transcript/message/2942458",
		"PostUrl" : "http://stackoverflow.com/a/9728068",
		"Site" : "stackoverflow.com",
		"Title" : "Finally, solved the problem. It appears VMware takes a very different pa...",
		"Body" : "<p>Finally, solved the problem. It appears VMware takes a very different path. The question was misconstrued.</p>\n\n<p>First, I traced the connection using WireShark, and at no point the server asks (need or  want) a certificate. However, VirtualCenter (VC) does provide a way to register a certificate as part of a connection and then use that certificate authenticate. For this to work, they provide a way to tunnel connections.</p>\n\n<p>The sequence I used is:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><p>First specify the URL to connect to as https://: (note the protocol is secure, but the port is not).</p></li>\n<li><p>The initial socket will be opened to the clear text port. But having https as the protocol will force calling my own SSLSocketFactory. In my socket factory, I get a call to my <code>public Socket createSocket(Socket s, String host, int port, boolean autoClose)</code> method, which allows me to convert my socket to SSLSocket to my taste.</p></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>My code essentially looks like:</p>\n\n<pre><code>@Override\npublic Socket createSocket(Socket s, String host, int port, boolean autoClose)\n    throws IOException {\n    s.setKeepAlive(true);\n    String connectReq = \"CONNECT /sdkTunnel HTTP/1.1\\r\\n\\r\\n\";\n    OutputStreamWriter writer = new OutputStreamWriter(socket.getOutputStream());\n    writer.write(connectReq, 0, connectReq.length());\n    writer.flush();\n    // In this initial response, all that matters is the http code. If\n    // it is 200, the rest can be ignored.\n    READ_AND_VERIFY_INITIAL_RESPONSE();\n    SSLSocket sock = (SSLSocket) origSslSockFactory\n        .createSocket(s, s.getInetAddress().getHostName(), s.getPort(), true);\n    // Depending on whether the caller actually does the handshake\n    // or not, you may need to call handshake here. In my case, I\n    // did not need to, since HTTPClient I am using calls the\n    // handshake. Axis does not call, so you may have to in that\n    // case.\n\n    // sock.startHandshake();\n    return sock;\n}\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>In the above block, origSslSockFactory is the SSLSocketFactory that got replaced by your implementation. In my case it was an instance of sun.security.ssl.SSLSocketFactoryImpl.</p>\n\n<p>After that procedure, calling ExtensionManager.setExtensionCertificate() succeeds. And subsequently, all calls to SessionManager.loginExtensionByCertificate() also succeeds. </p>\n\n<p>I wanted to post this as there seem to be a lot of questions about this.</p>",

	{
		"ReportLink" : "http://chat.meta.stackexchange.com/transcript/message/2942410",
		"PostUrl" : "http://worldbuilding.stackexchange.com/a/4808",
		"Site" : "worldbuilding.stackexchange.com",
		"Title" : "Many thanks to all of you! I think you all have good points, and the rea...",
		"Body" : "<p>Many thanks to all of you! I think you all have good points, and the real answer to my question would be a combination of these.</p>\n\n<p><strong>No: Economic or climatic (lack of ressources) pressures couldn't do the trick</strong><br>\nAs @WorldSpinner and @Vandroiy point out above, these types of pressure can only force a population drop for a limited amount of time. Indeed when the humans are less numerous, then the pressure fades and restrained fertility rise again.<br>\nAs the population is spread on a lot of planets, the risk for a great catastrophe to kill enough humans at once to get passed the minimal amount for specie perpetuation is also really unlikely.</p>\n\n<p><strong>No: It's all about culture!</strong><br>\nAs @Mark remarks in his answer, even if the mainstream culture discourages having lots of children, in time it would be replaced by the subcultures with higher fertility rates.<br>\nEven if global human fertility is decreasing, (for w/e reason) the individuals from the fertile subcultures willing to have children will try everything in order to do so, and probably succeed thanks to advanced science. (in vitro fecondation and so on) As @Vincent points out, individuals mostly do see their interest before such things as their specie's destiny.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Yes: It would require intervention of a greater institution or entity</strong><br>\nAs @WorldSpinner and @Vandroiy emphasise, the only way to go past these barriers is to postulate that an extremely well informed and patient institution or entity works in the shadows to lower the overall fertility (using viruses or chemicals) and break the most fertile subcultures. (using manipulation)<br>\nI think we proved here that this is necessary as else evolution or fertile subcultures (that we can see as a social mutation towards specie surviving) would always take over.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Alternative possibility: coincidences</strong><br>\nThe only other way is if an extremely unlucky chain of coincidences happens. For example first the economic pressure makes couples less eager to procreate, then a few catastrophic events dynamite the most fertile subcultures, while a very hardcore sect takes over...<br>\nWith the dramatic combination of all these economic, climatic and cultural factors, humanity could end up being a very infertile and fanatic small group of individuals.</p>",

In fact the spectral norm is defined as\n$$||A||_2 = \\sqrt{\\lambda_\\mathrm{max}(A^TA)}$$\nwhere $\\lambda_\\mathrm{max}(A^TA)$ denotes the maximum eigenvalue of $A^TA$.</p>\n\n<p>In my algorithm I'm using the GSL library to compute this $\\lambda_\\mathrm{max}$.\nOn it's <a href=\"https://www.gnu.org/software/gsl/manual/html_node/Eigensystems.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">manual</a> the GSL states that the algorithm used is a \"<em>symmetric bidiagonalization followed by QR reduction</em>\".</p>\n\n<p>My question is: given the absolute error of the components $A_{ij}$ how can I estimate the error on the largest eigenvalue of $A^TA$?\nCan you point me on the direction to further investigate the problem?</p>",

		"Title" : "If you need to remove the HTML but does not know if it actually contains...",
		"Body" : "<p>If you need to remove the HTML but does not know if it actually contains any HTML tags, you can't use the jQuery method directly because it returns empty wrapper for non-HTML text.</p>\n\n<pre><code>$('<div>Hello world</div>').text(); //returns \"Hello world\"\n$('Hello world').text(); //returns empty string \"\"\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>You must either wrap the text in valid HTML:</p>\n\n<pre><code>$('<div>' + 'Hello world' + '</div>').text();\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Or use method $.parseHTML() (since jQuery 1.8) that can handle both HTML and non-HTML text:</p>\n\n<pre><code>var html = $.parseHTML('Hello world'); //parseHTML return HTMLCollection\nvar text = $(html).text(); //use $() to get .text() method\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Plus parseHTML removes script tags completely which is useful as anti-hacking protection for user inputs.</p>\n\n<pre><code>$('<p>Hello world</p><script>console.log(document.cookie)</script>').text();\n//returns \"Hello worldconsole.log(document.cookie)\"\n\n$($.parseHTML('<p>Hello world</p><script>console.log(document.cookie)</script>')).text();\n//returns \"Hello world\"\n</code></pre>",

		"Title" : "jQuery is known to slow down with really large forms. See jQuery validat...",
		"Body" : "<p>jQuery is known to slow down with really large forms. See <a href=\"http://stackoverflow.com/q/5542014/3191599\">jQuery validate large forms - script running slowly</a> and <a href=\"http://stackoverflow.com/questions/5999374/long-form-using-jquery-validate-causes-ie-slow-script-warning\">Long form using jquery Validate causes IE slow script warning</a>.</p>\n\n<p>You have a couple of options. I'd approach them in this order:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><p>Customize or override jQuery's default validation function. The above 2 answers give some example of that, as well as this one: <a href=\"http://stackoverflow.com/questions/15589152/custom-method-with-jquery-validation-plugin\">Custom method with jQuery Validation plugin</a></p></li>\n<li><p>Paginate the form. Do you really need ~2000 checkboxes on a single form? Is there a way to split it up into multiple pages?</p></li>\n<li><p>Validate on the server side. If your application logic supports it, allow the form to be submitted even if invalid, run your validation logic on the server side, and then return the page with any validation messages if necessary.</p></li>\n</ul>",

		"Title" : "Here is a nice walkthrough by Dwight Goins. He uses a CSS file to \"reset...",
		"Body" : "<p>Here is a nice <a href=\"http://dgoins.wordpress.com/2011/07/07/the-960-grid-in-sharepoint-made-easy/\" rel=\"nofollow\">walkthrough by Dwight Goins</a>. He uses a CSS file to \"reset\" some default settings:</p>\n\n<pre><code><style type=\"text/css\">\n\n        /* fix scrolling on list pages */\n        #s4-bodyContainer {\n            position: relative;\n        }\n\n        /* hide body scrolling (SharePoint will handle) */\n        body {\n            height:100%;\n            overflow: scroll;\n\n           /* comment out width because we're using 960px instead */\n           /*width:100%;*/\n       }\n       </style>\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>He then placed the default content in a containing  and started his design.</p>\n\n<p>The falling pitfalls are called out:</p>\n\n<ol>\n<li><p>When working with page layouts, if you\u2019re not cognizant of the fact that your master page is using the 960 grid your layout will yield nasty vertical and horizontal scroll bars.</p></li>\n<li><p>When editing the page, if you place the web part adder and its corresponding controls in their normal positions, the runtime web part design experience becomes non-existent. Basically it becomes practically impossible to add, edit and remove web parts because there may not be any scrollbars and the design time controls flow off the page.</p></li>\n<li><p>Attempting to do this for the System Master pages is also impossible for the same reasons mentioned above, and the mere fact that system pages were designed to use the whole width of the page {width: 100%}. Leaving anything off would severely hinder system admin functionality.</p></li>\n</ol>",

		"PostUrl" : "http://stackoverflow.com/questions/28069255",
		"Site" : "stackoverflow.com",
		"Title" : "What is the proper way to organize those connections between classes in OOP",
		"Body" : "<p>There is some pattern in my code, that I have rather often, but never know how to organize those classes properly. Let's look at the most recent (simplified) example. It is written in C#, but I would assume that the \"solution\" generally applies to any OOP language. </p>\n\n<p>There are 3 classes: <code>Planet</code>, <code>Storage</code> and <code>Population</code>. </p>\n\n<p>Each <code>Planet</code> can have a Population and may have one or several Storages, with one being the main one. </p>\n\n<p>The <code>Population</code> among other things also has to eat, and for that draws the food from the main Storage of the Planet. This happens when the <code>Planet.Update()</code> is called, which then again also calls <code>Population.Update()</code>.</p>\n\n<p>Now my question is, how to properly model those connections between those 3 classes. I personally see a few options, but I'm not sure, which is the right one.</p>\n\n<p>a) Not make a separate Storage and Population class, but do it all in the Planet class. - This feels crude and unhandy, especially as those classes are quite big and merging all those, only because there is a very small overlap (small compared to the overall functionality of those classes), feels simply wrong.</p>\n\n<p>b) Each time <code>Population.Update()</code> is called, give the reference to the Storage as Parameter. - This is, what I am doing right now. It feels like a lot of redundancy and useless cluttering of the <code>Population.Update()</code>-signature though. Pretty much this parameter will be identical to the last call 99.99% of the time.</p>\n\n<p>c) Store permanently in the Population, from which Storage it should draw. - This targets the complaint I had with b), but brings new problems. Now I have to remember, that every time I change the main storage of the Planet, I also have to tell this to the Population. (or for whatever other reasons the used storage of the Planet changes) I have no doubt, I would remember doing that, if I were to change the Planet class in the next few weeks, but if I decide to work on it again in a year, I may run into troubles, because I forgot it.</p>\n\n<p>d) Store permanently in the Population, to which Planet it belongs, and add a method to the Planet, that returns a reference to its main storage. - This is sort of a mix between b) and c). It cleans up the signature of my <code>Population.Update()</code> and does not run into the troubles I see with c), but of course it requires a mostly redundant method call to get the <code>Storage</code> each time <code>Population.Update()</code> is called.</p>",

(When this line is left out, rotation performs as expected)\n        // When it is left in, the drone rotates but snaps back to it's original position on key release.\n        rigidbody.rotation = Quaternion.Euler (rigidbody.velocity.z, 0.0f, rigidbody.velocity.x * -tilt);\n\n        // Ascend.\n        if (Input.GetKey (\"t\")){\n            rigidbody.AddRelativeForce (Vector3.up * power);\n        }\n\n        // Descend.\n        if (Input.GetKey (\"g\")) {\n            rigidbody.AddRelativeForce (Vector3.down * power);\n        }\n\n        // Rotate clockwise.\n        if (Input.GetKey (\"h\")) {\n            transform.Rotate(0, 5, 0, Space.Self);\n        }\n\n        // Rotate anti-clockwise.\n        if (Input.GetKey (\"f\")) {\n            transform.Rotate(0, -5, 0, Space.Self);\n        }\n    }\n}\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Maybe also worth noting that when I leave the <strong>tilt</strong> line in, any rotation I apply to the drone in transform properties is not applied, when taken out, I can set the starting rotation fine.</p>",

		"Title" : "At least in the US, graduate admissions committees tend to look at many ...",
		"Body" : "<p>At least in the US, graduate admissions committees tend to look at many factors. The three \"big\" areas tend to be your recommendation letters, personal statement, and standardized scores. They probably will look at your CV as well. You might be able to make up for a deficit in one area with strengths in other areas. For example, admissions committees might favor an applicant with at least one published paper prior to his/her application, even if he/she does not have the best GPA or GRE scores out of the entire applicant pool. I am less familiar with admissions outside of the US.Unfortunately, there isn't any one magic formula to guarantee admission to any program.</p>\n\n<p>That being said, I think you are correct in wondering how your GRE score will impact your chances of admission. Assuming that you took the most updated form of the GRE (where the range is 130-170 instead of 200-800 for each section), your score is quite low since you scored 35 points above the absolute minimum score. Most competitive graduate programs claim that successful applicants have GRE scores in at least the 50th percentile. As such, your low GRE score would likely be a major red flag for these programs. However, other programs tend to overlook GRE scores entirely (they will say you don't need to submit them) or weight them fairly low.</p>\n\n<p>Is there a way that you can postpone your applications and retake the GRE? If not, you need to put together the best application possible, which means putting extra effort and attention into the other parts of your application, like your personal statement. You might also consider applying to programs that explicitly do not require standardized scores or weigh them low, which means that if the GRE is the only weak point of your application, you're likely fine. Again, there is no way of any of us knowing what you can do to guarantee admission, but in your situation, I would suggest that you make the things still within your control the best they can be.</p>",

		"Body" : "<h2>POSIX <code>sh</code> + GNU <code>find</code> + GNU <code>mv</code> 67 ASCII bytes + one <em>(literal)</em> space</h2>\n\n<pre><code>find    -d  -exec   sh  -cf 'IFS=\\ ;IFS=_   set $0;mv   --b=t   \"$0\"    \"$*\"'   {}  \\;\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>I don't know if it fits, but with this any <em>sequence</em> of spaces is elided to a single <code>_</code> - I like it anyway. Actually any <em>sequence</em> but leading/trailing spaces that is - those are automatically truncated <em>(which is also, I think, a beneficial behavior)</em>. Thanks to Gilles for pointing this out. </p>\n\n<p>This just uses the internal field separator to separate fields.</p>\n\n<p>It's fairly... <em>chatty</em>...</p>\n\n<p>...oh man. 	{
		"ReportLink" : "http://chat.meta.stackexchange.com/transcript/message/2935354",
		"PostUrl" : "http://stackoverflow.com/a/28036791",
		"Site" : "stackoverflow.com",
		"Title" : "Well, I planned to just write the relevant parts of the program but I en...",
		"Body" : "<p>Well, I planned to just write the relevant parts of the program but I ended up writing an entire working program instead. Since I don't know how much Python you know I'm just going to explain the entire program; sorry if I have a somewhat pedantic and/or pompous air. Feel free to just skip to the bottom and copy the code.</p>\n\n<p>The code I wrote demonstrates 4 Python idioms: object oriented design, bytearray/string slicing and formatting, the xrange() function, and error catching.</p>\n\n<p>I think that csv would not be a good angle to approach the problem with. I opted to store the data as a text table. Each line takes the following form:\n30 characters name | 10 characters total score | 9 characters attempts | 1 newline\nThe benefit of this is that each line is exactly 50 characters wide. So, unlike the csv approach, we don't have to scan through for commas to find relevent data; we just go through the data in increments of 50 characters. This makes for much more readable code, and it's not like text storage space is at a premium these days.</p>\n\n<p>Example: Chell R earned 42 points in 5 attempts becomes:</p>\n\n<pre><code>\"                       Chell R        42        5\\n\"\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Since we're going to be sorting  this data later, it would be advantageous to store both the student's name and his/her score in an object. This object makes sorting much simpler; because the name is permanently attatched to the score, we don't have to worry about making sure the name data follows the score data as the data is sorted. It just happens implicitly.</p>\n\n<p>This is the first portion of the code:</p>\n\n<pre><code>import time, random, operator\ndirectory_name = r\"C:\\Users\\YOU\\yourDirectoryHere\\\\\"\n#When you change the directory name, be SURE to include\n#the double backslash at the end.\ndatafile = open(directory_name + \"scores.txt\")\ndata = bytearray(datafile.read())\ndatafile.close()\n\nclass entry():\n    def __init__(self, i):\n        #i is the location of the student's entry in the data.\n        global data\n        self.name = data[i:i + 30]\n        self.total = int(data[i + 30:i + 40])\n        self.attempts = int(data[i + 40:i + 49])\n        if self.attempts:\n            self.average = float(self.total) / self.attempts\n        else: self.average = 0.0\n\n    def update_score(self, score, i):\n        global data, directory_name\n        self.total += score\n        self.attempts += 1\n        self.average = float(self.total) / self.attempts\n        data[i + 30: i + 40] = \"%10i\" % self.total\n        data[i + 40: i + 49] = \"%9i\" % self.attempts\n        datafile = open(directory_name + \"scores.txt\",'w')\n        datafile.write(data)\n        datafile.close()\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>The method defined under <strong>init</strong> is known as a magic method. This means that unlike the regular method update_score, you don't call the method yourself. It's automatically called by Python; in this case it's called when an entry object is created.</p>\n\n<p>Five things to point out:\n1: Just to quickly explain a syntax annoyance, each method must have self as the first argument and each variable stored in the object needs a self. prefix.</p>\n\n<p>2: Notice that the data read from the file is converted to the bytearray type. Bytearrays are useful because unlike strings they are mutable, so we can update students' scores when neccessary without inefficiently recreating the entire string. I opted to pass data as a global variable instead of a regular argument in order to avoid having to pass it through several layers of functions.</p>\n\n<p>3: The expression foo = bar[x:y] is a slice operation. This means \"Fill variable foo with characters x through y-1 of bar\". I used it in the <strong>init</strong> function in order to initialize the entry's name and score values. The reverse also works, as seen in the update_score method.</p>\n\n<p>4: Another useful trick for string or bytearray formatting inherits from C. Since each total score entry must take up 10 characters in order to keep each entry 50 characters wide, use the string \"%10i\" % self.total in order to force the interger to a 10 character width.</p>\n\n<p>5: Finally, just a quick note that I wrote float(self.total) / self.attempts. Dividing an integer by an integer results in a rounded, inaccurate integer.</p>\n\n<p>The next part of the program is the main play() function, which calls find_entry():</p>\n\n<pre><code>def find_entry(name):\n    global data\n    for i in xrange(0,len(data),50):\n        if data[i:i + 30] == \"%30s\" % name:\n            return i\n    print \"Name not found. Please check the spelling of your name.\"\n    print \"If you spelled your name correctly please ask your teacher for help.\"\n    return None\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>The xrange function is first seen in the find_entry function. This provides a much more readable, pythonic way to iterate than while loops. \"for i in xrange(0,len(data),50):\" is equivalent to. \"i = 0; While i < len(data): ... i += 50. Anyway, all it does is go through the data 50 characters at a time (since each entry is 50 characters wide) and check if the first 30 characters match up with the inputted name. (Note that I use data[i:i + 30] == \"%30s\" % name. The inputted name must be pumped up to 30 characters, otherwise the equality operator will always fail). It returns the index i of the found entry if successful and returns None to indicate failure.</p>\n\n<p>Next we'll examine the main play() function:</p>\n\n<pre><code>def play():\n    global data\n    entry_num = None\n    while entry_num == None:\n        entry_num = find_entry(raw_input(\"Please enter your name and surname initial (e.g. William G): \"))\n\n    student_entry = entry(entry_num)\n    score = 0\n    for i in xrange(10): #same as xrange(0,10,1)\n        score += question()\n\n    student_entry.update_score(score, entry_num)\n    print \"Your score this time was %i / 10\" % score\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>We see here that the fact that find_entry returns None upon failure is put to good use. The while loop means the program keeps on trying until a valid name is inputted. Also note the use of the raw_input function. This forces Python to interpret the input as a string. This'll make more sense in the next function, the question function:</p>\n\n<pre><code>def question():\n    n1 = random.randint(1,9)\n    n2 = random.randint(1,9)\n    ops = {'+': operator.add, '-': operator.sub, 'x': operator.mul}\n    op = random.choice(ops.keys())\n    answer = raw_input(\"What is %i %s %i?  \" % (n1, op, n2))\n    try: \n        answer = int(answer)\n        if answer == ops[op](n1, n2):\n            print \"Well done\"\n            return 1\n        else:\n            print \"incorrect, %i %s %i = %i\" % (n1, op, n2, ops[op](n1,n2))\n            return 0\n    except ValueError:\n        print \"'%s' does not appear to be a number.\" % answer\n        return 0\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>I pretty much just copied your code verbatim for this part. The only major difference is the addition of the try... except statement and the use of raw_input() in lieu of input(). The issue with input() is that it's pretty unsafe, since Python is free to interpret its input as any type, including a variable name, a bogus input can wreck all sorts of havoc. raw_input is much safer: since Python always interprets the input as a string the programmer gets the right to interpret the input and anticipate errors. In this case, the try... except statement tries to convert the inputted string to an integer with int(). int() raises ValueError if it fails to convert the string to an integer, so an except ValueError statement would execute instead upon failure, communicating the failure to the user and allowing the program to recover instead of crashing.</p>\n\n<p>Now that that's dealt with, we can move on to the actually interesting part of the question: sorting the entries.</p>\n\n<p>Going back to the entry() class definition, there are two additional magic methods which facilitate leaderboard creation, <strong>cmp</strong> and <strong>str</strong>:</p>\n\n<pre><code>class entry():\n    def __init__(self, i):\n        ...\n\n    def __cmp__(self, other):\n        return self.average - other.average\n\n    def __str__(self):\n        return \"%s | %2.2f\" % (self.name, self.average)\n\n    def update_score(self, score, i):\n        ...\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>The <strong>cmp</strong> method is called when Python needs to compare two entries. Since we want the leaderboards to be sorted by average score, not alphabetically or by total score, we return a comparison of this entry's average with the other entry's average (Python interprets a negative return value as self < other and a positive return value as self > other)</p>\n\n<p>The <strong>str</strong> method is what's called when str(a) or print(a) is encountered, where a is an entry type. Since we now must format two pieces of data, the student's name and average, we put the two variables in a tuple after the % sign. The %2.2f tells Python to print a floating point number with only 2 digit after the decimal point; any further digits are ignored.</p>\n\n<p>All the work was done writing the methods. Writing the leaderboard() function thus becomes a trivial affair:</p>\n\n<pre><code>def leaderboard():\n    global data\n    entries = []\n    for i in xrange(0, len(data),50):\n        entries += [entry(i)]\n\n    entries.sort()\n    entries.reverse()\n\n    for i in entries:\n        print i\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>We see the beauty of object oriented programming at work here. The xrange loop calls the entry's <strong>init</strong> method over and over again, populating the list with entries. This somewhat complex function is safely stowed away in the entry class declaration, keeping the leaderboard function clean and easy to read. Next, the sort() method of Python's built in list object is called, so we don't need to reinvent the wheel writing another sorting algorithm. This calls our <strong>cmp</strong> function, ensuring that Python will correctly sort the entries by average score as intended. Next, we reverse() the list, since we want the highest scores first. Again, no need to write this function ourselves; it comes along with the list type in Python. Finally, we print the leaderboard. This calls the entry class's <strong>str</strong> function, so in the leaderboard function itself we don't need to worry about finding the correct data in the data file. Nice and clean.</p>\n\n<p>Pretty much done here, now all there's to do is write the main loop:</p>\n\n<pre><code>while True:\n    print \"\"\"\\\nWelcome to Simple-Maths Questions program\nPlease type one of the following:\nPlay | Leaderboard | Exit\"\"\"\n    command = raw_input()\n    command = command.upper()\n    if command in \"PLAY\":\n        play()\n    elif command in \"LEADERBOARD\":\n        leaderboard()\n    elif command in \"EXIT\":\n        break #You don't have to call quit() to terminate the program, just reach EOF.\n    elif command in \"ADD NAME\":\n        add_student()\n    else:\n        print \"unknown command\"\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Again, raw_input() is safer than input(). The keyword is converted to all caps and only finds whether the input is in the keyword, so the input is not case sensitive and there's no need to type the full keyword (This was a timesaver for debugging). Also, there's the hidden command \"ADD NAME\"; I didn't feel like explaining that function. And that's, uh, pretty much all I have to say.</p>\n\n<p>And here is the completed code:</p>\n\n<pre><code>import time, random, operator\ndirectory_name = r\"C:\\Users\\YOU\\yourDirectoryHere\\\\\"\n#When you change the directory name, be SURE to include\n#the double backslash at the end. (and keep the r)\ndatafile = open(directory_name + \"scores.txt\")\ndata = bytearray(datafile.read())\ndatafile.close()\n\nbackup_directory = directory_name\ndef backup():\n    #Note: I didn't explain this function. It just randomly\n    #makes backups of the data file in case something unexpected happens.\n    global data, backup_directory\n    datafile = open(backup_directory + str(int(time.time())) + '.txt', 'w')\n    datafile.write(\"Remove this timestamp, message, and newline before restoring this data %s\\n\" % time.asctime())\n    datafile.write(data)\n    datafile.close()\n\nclass entry():\n    def __init__(self, i):\n        #i is the location of the student's entry in the data.\n        global data\n        self.name = data[i:i + 30]\n        self.total = int(data[i + 30:i + 40])\n        self.attempts = int(data[i + 40:i + 49])\n        if self.attempts:\n            self.average = float(self.total) / self.attempts\n        else: self.average = 0.0\n\n    def __cmp__(self, other):\n        #BUGGED CODE return self.average - other.average\n        #FIXED BELOW\n        if self.average > other.average: return 1\n        elif self.average < other.average: return -1\n        else: return 0\n\n    def __str__(self):\n        return \"%s | %2.2f\" % (self.name, self.average)\n\n    def update_score(self, score, i):\n        global data, directory_name\n        self.total += score\n        self.attempts += 1\n        self.average = float(self.total) / self.attempts\n        data[i + 30: i + 40] = \"%10i\" % self.total\n        data[i + 40: i + 49] = \"%9i\" % self.attempts\n        datafile = open(directory_name + \"scores.txt\",'w')\n        datafile.write(data)\n        datafile.close()\n\n        if not random.randrange(5):\n            backup()\n\n\ndef find_entry(name):\n    global data\n    for i in xrange(0,len(data),50):\n        if data[i:i + 30] == \"%30s\" % name:\n            return i\n    print \"Name not found. Please check the spelling of your name.\"\n    print \"If you spelled your name correctly please ask your teacher for help.\"\n    return None\n\ndef question():\n    n1 = random.randint(1,9)\n    n2 = random.randint(1,9)\n    ops = {'+': operator.add, '-': operator.sub, 'x': operator.mul}\n    op = random.choice(ops.keys())\n    answer = raw_input(\"What is %i %s %i?  \" % (n1, op, n2))\n    try: \n        answer = int(answer)\n        if answer == ops[op](n1, n2):\n            print \"Well done\"\n            return 1\n        else:\n            print \"incorrect, %i %s %i = %i\" % (n1, op, n2, ops[op](n1,n2))\n            return 0\n    except:\n        print \"'%s' does not appear to be a number.\" % answer\n        return 0\n\ndef play():\n    global data\n    entry_num = None\n    while entry_num == None:\n        entry_num = find_entry(raw_input(\"Please enter your name and surname initial (e.g. William G): \"))\n\n    student_entry = entry(entry_num)\n    score = 0\n    for i in xrange(10):\n        score += question()\n\n    student_entry.update_score(score, entry_num)\n    print \"Your score this time was %i / 10\" % score\n\ndef leaderboard():\n    global data\n    entries = []\n    for i in xrange(0, len(data),50):\n        entries += [entry(i)]\n\n    entries.sort()\n    entries.reverse()\n\n    for i in entries:\n        print i\n\ndef add_student():\n    #This wasn't explained either. It just appends a properly formatted 50 character\n    #long entry to the bytearray, initialized with the inputted name and zeroes.\n    global data\n    while True:\n        student = raw_input(\"Add a student, press enter to quit: \")\n        if student:\n            cancel = raw_input(\"Confirm '%s'. Press enter to confirm, any key to cancel: \" % student)\n            if not cancel:\n                data += bytearray(\"%30s%10i%9i\\n\" % (student,0,0))\n            else: print \"cancelled\"\n        else:\n            break\n    datafile = open(directory_name + \"scores.txt\",'w')\n    datafile.write(data)\n    datafile.close()\n\nwhile True:\n    print \"\"\"\\\nWelcome to Simple-Maths Questions program\nPlease type one of the following:\nPlay | Leaderboard | Exit\"\"\"\n    command = raw_input()\n    command = command.upper()\n    if command in \"PLAY\":\n        play()\n    elif command in \"LEADERBOARD\":\n        leaderboard()\n    elif command in \"EXIT\":\n        break\n    elif command in \"ADD NAME\":\n        add_student()\n    else:\n        print \"unknown command\"\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Note: I haven't exactly exhaustively bug tested this, so please do a bit of testing yourself to make sure this works.</p>\n\n<p>NOTE 2: Amended cmp function; .sort behaved erratically with close floating pt. numbers.</p>",

		"Body" : "<p>In the case of rack equipment in data centers, we put the target port and source port on every label - preferably in two lines.  It's reversed on the opposite end of the cable.  For example if I have a server CALPROD1 and I'm plugging into the iLo and on the other end I'm coming from switch CALSW035, blade 3, port 2, the labels would look like this...</p>\n\n<p>SERVER SIDE:</p>\n\n<p><strong>CALPROD1 /ilo</strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>CALSW035 /3.2</strong></p>\n\n<p>SWITCH SIDE:</p>\n\n<p><strong>CALSW35 /3.2</strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>CALPROD1 /ilo</strong></p>\n\n<p>There are several benefits to this.  Firstly, if service has to be performed and the cables need to be removed (like a chassis has to be pulled to replace a board or add memory, etc.) the engineer knows exactly where the cable came from and where to plug it back in.  From a tracing perspective, you know exactly where the this cable is going on the other end - patch panel, switch, another server, etc.  Sometimes we even put the cabinet info. Example: <strong>[A42] CALPROD1 / ilo</strong></p>\n\n<p>I merge all my labels from spreadsheet using the USB to a brother p-touch.  Their extra sticky labels are great in high-heat situations (like the back of servers) and their flexible ID tape is great for creating flags by wrapping cables.  If you use the \"regular\" labels in high heat, the lamination comes undone because it wants to return to flat while the white backer remains wrapped.</p>\n\n<p>When you have 40+ flags to put on, (often after you've already cabled stuff up), it's a real pain to get two sticky things to line up perfectly straight and without any creases or wrinkles.  The flags hardly ever come out like they look in the pictures.  <strong>IF ANY OF YOU HAVE A TRICK TO DOING FLAGS, PLEASE ADVISE!!!</strong></p>\n\n<p>I'd love to label parallel to the cable and then put a clear shrink sleeve over it but we cannot use anything like a heat gun or torch in a production data center.  Plus cables need to be unplugged in order to thread the sleeve.  Often times we're under a time crunch so cable dressing and labeling come after the system's spinning.</p>\n\n<p>Panduit flags are awesome to stick labels on (even the basic labels).  have to zip tie them but it's quick and easy to do even on active connections.  Cables are no longer \"snag less\" and Panduit tags cost more that the CAT5e cables themselves!  WTF?  Can't these be made overseas for practically free?</p>\n\n<p>Hope this is helpful.</p>\n\n<p>Great discussion!  Thanks!</p>",

		"Body" : "<p>I wanted to comment but since i can't...</p>\n\n<p>Are you talking about the energy generation to produce fertilizer ? Then of course you can go non-fossil sources...you can use the sun the wind the water i think that if it is a closed environment you can even use the methane you generate to generate your own power</p>\n\n<p>But what you should ask yourself is do you really need industrialized fertilizer at all? Look to the nature plants have been there in abundance for a long time you can get all you need free from the nature.</p>\n\n<p>The overall fertility and viability of the soil, rather than the application of fertilizers as quick fixes, is at the very heart of organic gardening.</p>\n\n<p>Many organic materials serve as both fertilizers and soil conditioners\u2014they feed both soils and plants. This is one of the most important differences between a chemical approach and an organic approach toward soil care and fertilizing. Soluble chemical fertilizers contain mineral salts that plant roots can absorb quickly. However, these salts do not provide a food source for soil microorganisms and earthworms, and will even repel earthworms because they acidify the soil. Over time, soils treated only with synthetic chemical fertilizers lose organic matter and the all-important living organisms that help to build a quality soil. As soil structure declines and water-holding capacity diminishes, more and more of the chemical fertilizer applied will leach through the soil. In turn, it will take ever-increasing amounts of chemicals to stimulate plant growth. When you use organic fertilizers, you avoid throwing your soil into this kind of crisis condition.</p>\n\n<p>Use earthworms they are really good for the health of any soil and they are a free infinite fertilizer productor.</p>\n\n<p>Also you can try to plant a few spare leguminous plants on your farm because they take the nitrogen from air and put it on the ground avaible for other plant's to use if did right you won't  need to add nitrogen never again just le the nature do the job!</p>\n\n<p>I will stop here you can find much more about organics fertilizer and how to organic care not only your plants but your soil too on google</p>",

		"Title" : "What's the model representation for the first difference of a local level model?",
		"Body" : "<p>This is my first exercise for space state models and I've a few questions I'd need to resolve before I actually start doing the exercise. Unfortunately, I'm self teaching (I have no professor to ask) and I'm afraid there's no solution companion for Durbin and Koopman (2012)!</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p><strong><a href=\"http://www.oxfordscholarship.com/view/10.1093/acprof:oso/9780199641178.001.0001/acprof-9780199641178-chapter-2?rskey=FZDLQi&result=3\" rel=\"nofollow\">Exercise 2.13.1 from Time Series Analysis by State Space Methods Second Edition</a></strong></p>\n  \n  <p>Consider the local level model (2.3).</p>\n  \n  <p>(a) Give the model representation for $x_t = y_t - y_{t-1}$, for $t = 2, ..., n$.</p>\n  \n  <p>(b) Show that the model for $x_t$ in (a) can have the same statistical properties as the model given by $x_t = \\epsilon_t + \\theta \\epsilon_{t-1}$ where $\\epsilon \\sim N(0, \\sigma_{\\epsilon}^2)$, .......</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>For the record, the local level model (2.3) is given by:</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>$y_t = \\alpha_t + \\epsilon_t \\quad\\quad \\epsilon_t \\sim N(0, \\sigma_{\\epsilon}^2)$</p>\n  \n  <p>$\\alpha_{t+1} = \\alpha_t + \\eta_t \\quad\\quad \\eta_t \\sim N(0, \\sigma_{\\eta}^2)$</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p><strong>Doubts about (a)</strong></p>\n\n<p>First of all, the model proposed in (a) looks like noise (which makes perfect sense since it's the first difference of a random walk). Is the following representation correct?</p>\n\n<p>$$ x_t = y_t - y_{t-1} = \\alpha_t + \\epsilon_t - \\alpha_{t-1} - \\epsilon_{t-1} $$\n$$ x_t = \\alpha_{t-1} + \\eta_{t-1} + \\epsilon_t - \\alpha_{t-1} - \\epsilon_{t-1} $$\n$$ x_t = \\eta_{t-1} + \\epsilon_{t} - \\epsilon_{t-1}  $$</p>\n\n<p>This makes me doubt. First, state disturbance $\\eta_{t-1}$ is now part of the observation equation. Second, what does the state equation mean now that the observation equation doesn't relate to the unobserved states $\\alpha_t$? Third, and somehow related, what's the mean unobserved state now that $\\alpha_t$ isn't anymore on the formula? Zero?</p>\n\n<p><strong>Doubts about (b)</strong></p>\n\n<p>Additionaly, I wonder how to show that models have the same statistical properties. What do you have to prove to say they're the same? Same expected value and variance of observation $x_t$, unobserved state $\\alpha_t$, prediction error $v_t = x_t - a_t $, filtered unobserved state, updated unobserved state, etc.? Since all random variables are Normal, I guess showing the first two moments match is enough, but a) what distribution (marginal, conditionals, conditionals on what?) of b) what variables (observed, hidden state, prediction error, etc.) should be equal?</p>\n\n<p>Any comment is much appreciated!</p>",
