	{
		"ReportLink" : "http://chat.meta.stackexchange.com/transcript/message/2934982",
		"PostUrl" : "http://serverfault.com/a/177256",
		"Site" : "serverfault.com",
		"Title" : "Preamble\n\nThis worked for me. If there is a simpler way, I am sure you w...",
		"Body" : "<h2>Preamble</h2>\n\n<p>This worked for me. If there is a simpler way, I am sure you will let me know.</p>\n\n<p>In theory these steps should work for any linux distribution, you just need to find the original configure options that are used to compile apache for your distro. Perhaps you could add comments to this answer on where you found the options.</p>\n\n<p>The important option is:</p>\n\n<pre><code>--enable-layout=Debian</code></pre>\n\n<p>Debian can be changed to any one of the supported layouts in config.layout file in the apache build directory, the options are defined as:</p>\n\n<pre><code><Layout x>\n...\n</Layout></code></pre>\n\n<p>Where x would be the layout option. Try googling \"--enable-layout=x\" where x is your distribution to find your options. Try find the original options used by your distro and not some random suggestions.</p>\n\n<p>EDIT: As mentioned by faker the problem with this is that when you upgrade using apt and there is a new version of apache2, the compiled version will be overwritten. His suggestion of building a new deb is a good one. Unfortunately due to various deb dependency issues that are too much work to get around I have not been able to do so. However I would suggest that you try that route first, this should help you:</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://blog.wpkg.org/2014/06/29/building-apache-2-4-x-deb-packages-for-debian-wheezy-7-x/\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://blog.wpkg.org/2014/06/29/building-apache-2-4-x-deb-packages-for-debian-wheezy-7-x/</a></p>\n\n<p>I've opted to keep it as is, however I have set a hold on apache2 so it is not upgraded till I am ready to release the hold. Alternatively you could just remove apache from the machine and add it again when you are ready.</p>\n\n<p>To hold:</p>\n\n<pre><code>sudo apt-mark hold apache2</code></pre>\n\n<p>To release hold:</p>\n\n<pre><code>sudo apt-mark unhold apache2</code></pre>\n\n<p>I would also suggest that you make a clone of the server you wish to change, work through the process on the clone and get it working before trying it on a production env. Breaking apache for a day or longer on a prod environment is not a stress you need in your life. This is where virtual machines are great, take a snapshot and create a new instance from the snapshot. Or replicate the environment you wish to change and make the changes there.</p>\n\n<p>I use digital ocean, they rock, use this link to get $10 off your subscription. Disclaimer I get $25 off mine:</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://www.digitalocean.com/?refcode=9287fc77c7ae\" rel=\"nofollow\">https://www.digitalocean.com/?refcode=9287fc77c7ae</a></p>\n\n<h2>Here is how to do it on ubuntu as promised</h2>\n\n<p>This assumes that you already have the default apache version installed on your system by having previously run:</p>\n\n<pre><code>sudo apt-get install apache2</code></pre>\n\n<p>and you have run</p>\n\n<pre><code>sudo apt-get upgrade</code></pre>\n\n<p>To upgrade all packages to the latest, including apache.</p>\n\n<p>If there have been major changes in config from your version to the latest version of apache you would need to make those changes yourself. This can take a while, hence the suggestion of trying this on a server clone as mentioned in the preamble.</p>\n\n<p>You need to install the dependencies to do the build</p>\n\n<pre><code>sudo apt-get build-dep apache2</code></pre>\n\n<p>You need to download the apache source and unzip it, this will be referred to as the build directory.</p>\n\n<p>Backup your current configuration: DON'T SKIP THIS STEP</p>\n\n<pre><code>sudo cp -r /etc/apache2 ~/apache2_conf_back</code></pre>\n\n<p>You need to establish what your release code name is:</p>\n\n<pre><code>sudo cat /etc/lsb-release</code></pre>\n\n<p>Mine is trusty</p>\n\n<pre><code>DISTRIB_ID=Ubuntu\nDISTRIB_RELEASE=14.04\nDISTRIB_CODENAME=trusty\nDISTRIB_DESCRIPTION=\"Ubuntu 14.04.1 LTS\"</code></pre>\n\n<p>You should then be able to replace the 2 occurrences of the word \"trusty\" in the following url to get the options used to build your release's version of apache</p>\n\n<p>bazaar.launchpad.net/~ubuntu-branches/ubuntu/trusty/apache2/trusty/view/head:/debian/rules</p>\n\n<p>I used the options defined for the variables \"AP2_COMMON_CONFARGS\" and \"AP2_worker_CONFARGS\". Additionally I added the options:</p>\n\n<pre><code>--with-pcre=/usr \\\n--enable-mpms-shared=all \\\n--enable-unixd=static \\</code></pre>\n\n<p>As I ended up trying a few times to get this right, I created the following file in the apache build directory which I ran each time. Call it myconfig.sh</p>\n\n<pre><code>#!/bin/bash\n./configure \\\n--with-pcre=/usr \\\n--enable-mpms-shared=all \\\n--enable-unixd=static \\\n--enable-layout=Debian --enable-so \\\n--with-program-name=apache2  \\\n--with-ldap=yes --with-ldap-include=/usr/include \\\n--with-ldap-lib=/usr/lib \\\n--with-suexec-caller=www-data \\\n--with-suexec-bin=/usr/lib/apache2/suexec \\\n--with-suexec-docroot=/var/www \\\n--with-suexec-userdir=public_html \\\n--with-suexec-logfile=/var/log/apache2/suexec.log \\\n--with-suexec-uidmin=100 \\\n--enable-suexec=shared \\\n--enable-log-config=static --enable-logio=static \\\n--enable-version=static \\\n--with-apr=/usr/bin/apr-1-config \\\n--with-apr-util=/usr/bin/apu-1-config \\\n--with-pcre=yes \\\n--enable-pie \\\n--enable-authn-alias=shared --enable-authnz-ldap=shared  \\\n--enable-disk-cache=shared --enable-cache=shared \\\n--enable-mem-cache=shared --enable-file-cache=shared \\\n--enable-cern-meta=shared --enable-dumpio=shared --enable-ext-filter=shared \\\n--enable-charset-lite=shared --enable-cgi=shared \\\n--enable-dav-lock=shared --enable-log-forensic=shared \\\n--enable-ldap=shared --enable-proxy=shared \\\n--enable-proxy-connect=shared --enable-proxy-ftp=shared \\\n--enable-proxy-http=shared --enable-proxy-ajp=shared \\\n--enable-proxy-scgi=shared \\\n--enable-proxy-balancer=shared --enable-ssl=shared \\\n--enable-authn-dbm=shared --enable-authn-anon=shared \\\n--enable-authn-dbd=shared --enable-authn-file=shared \\\n--enable-authn-default=shared --enable-authz-host=shared \\\n--enable-authz-groupfile=shared --enable-authz-user=shared \\\n--enable-authz-dbm=shared --enable-authz-owner=shared \\\n--enable-authnz-ldap=shared --enable-authz-default=shared \\\n--enable-auth-basic=shared --enable-auth-digest=shared \\\n--enable-dbd=shared --enable-deflate=shared \\\n--enable-include=shared --enable-filter=shared \\\n--enable-env=shared --enable-mime-magic=shared \\\n--enable-expires=shared --enable-headers=shared \\\n--enable-ident=shared --enable-usertrack=shared \\\n--enable-unique-id=shared --enable-setenvif=shared \\\n--enable-status=shared \\\n--enable-autoindex=shared --enable-asis=shared \\\n--enable-info=shared --enable-cgid=shared \\\n--enable-dav=shared --enable-dav-fs=shared \\\n--enable-vhost-alias=shared --enable-negotiation=shared \\\n--enable-dir=shared --enable-imagemap=shared \\\n--enable-actions=shared --enable-speling=shared \\\n--enable-userdir=shared --enable-alias=shared \\\n--enable-rewrite=shared --enable-mime=shared \\\n--enable-substitute=shared  --enable-reqtimeout=shared;\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Stop the current apache</p>\n\n<pre><code>/etc/init.d/apache2 stop</code></pre>\n\n<p>To build and install apache, run the following commands in the build directory</p>\n\n<pre><code>./myconfig.sh\nmake\nmake install</code></pre>\n\n<p>Restore your apache config. I HOPE YOU BACKED YOUR CONFIG UP AS DESCRIBED EARLIER</p>\n\n<pre><code>sudo rm -rf /etc/apache2\nsudo cp -r ~/apache2_conf_back /etc/apache2</code></pre>\n\n<p>I needed to make the include paths absolute in /etc/apache2/apache2.conf, the following commands do this in vim</p>\n\n<pre><code>:%s/^IncludeOptional /IncludeOptional \\/etc\\/apache2\\//</code></pre>\n\n<pre><code>:%s/^Include /Include \\/etc\\/apache2\\// /</code></pre>\n\n<p>I also needed to change the path to the envvars in /usr/sbin/apache2ctl to /etc/apache2/envvars</p>\n\n<p>Then restart apache</p>\n\n<pre>/etc/init.d/apache2 start</pre>\n\n<p>Hopefully that works for you, if there are any syntax errors please let me know so I can fix them. Much of them were rewritten from memory.</p>\n\n<p>Good Luck!</p>\n\n<p>Special thanks to jrwren for his post that was the missing piece to my puzzle:</p>\n\n<p>how-to-build-configure-options-latest-apache-on-ubuntu</p>",

		"Body" : "<p>Following the guide lines of @sven (thank you so much!) I've solved my question and I post the answer for it helps somebody.</p>\n\n<p>First of all, I've checked id  <code>getent passwd</code> was showing LDAP users or only local users. In my case, it shows only local users.</p>\n\n<p>Second install if you don't have it, <code>authconfig</code>: <code>yum -y install authconfig</code></p>\n\n<p>Write the following command to enable it:</p>\n\n<pre><code>authconfig --passalgo=sha256 --enablelocauthorize \\\n--enablemkhomedir --enableldap --enableldapauth \\\n--ldapserver=ldap://127.0.0.1 --ldapbasedn=dc=example,dc=com \\\n--enableshadow --update\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Console write in my case:</p>\n\n<pre><code>getsebool:  SELinux is disabled\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Then configure start on boot like this:</p>\n\n<pre><code>chkconfig nslcd on\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Start service:</p>\n\n<p><code>service nslcd start</code> or <code>systemctl start  nslcd.service</code></p>\n\n<p>Try getent:</p>\n\n<pre><code>getent passwd user1\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Console write the LDAP user:</p>\n\n<pre><code>user1:*:1005:1005:user1:/var/www/html:/bin/bash\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>I hope that it is well.</p>",

		"Site" : "emacs.stackexchange.com",
		"Title" : "\n  The solution would seem to be to create individual entries for every ...",
		"Body" : "<blockquote>\n  <p>The solution would seem to be to create individual entries for every occurrence of the recurring event, which will be tedious and inefficient. </p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>Why?  It would be the way to gain maximum control and AFAIK this is required for repeated events that you want to transfer via e.g. <code>org-caldav.el</code>.  The reason is that you need an UID (<em>U</em>nique) for each event to be able to consistently track them (though <code>ox-ical.el</code> does provide such an UID for repeated events set up with e.g. <code>org-class</code> they are ignored by at least <code>org-caldav.el</code>).</p>\n\n<p>Fortunately, <code>org-clone-subtree-with-time-shift</code> has been part of Emacs for a good many years.  It will set up <em>n</em> headings for you with a timeshift, like <code>+1w</code>.</p>\n\n<p>Example</p>\n\n<pre><code>(with-temp-buffer\n  (save-excursion (insert \"* foo\\n<2015-01-21 mi\u00E9>\"))\n  (org-clone-subtree-with-time-shift 2 \"+1w\")\n  (buffer-substring-no-properties (point-min) (point-max)))\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Output</p>\n\n<pre><code> * foo \n <2015-01-21 mi\u00E9>\n * foo\n <2015-01-28 mi\u00E9>\n * foo\n <2015-02-04 mi\u00E9>\n</code></pre>",

		"Title" : "Estimating the effect of regression fitting error",
		"Body" : "<p>Suppose I have a number of random variables $X,Y,\\ldots$, and we can assume the joint distribution of these variables is known in advance. I also have an unknown function $f(x,y,\\ldots)$ with corresponding input parameters. The values of $f()$ are obtained by experiment, and we can assume that $f()$ is repeatable (so if I repeat the experiment with the same inputs I get the same answer).</p>\n\n<p>I then take $N$ samples from the random variables, and for each sample $x_i,y_i,\\ldots$ obtain (from an experiment) observations $f_i=f(x_i,y_i,\\ldots)$. I then use least squares regression to estimate a polynomial approximation $\\hat{f}$ to $f$ based on the sample data and observations.</p>\n\n<p>There are a number of well established tests for assessing the goodness of fit/estimation error of $\\hat{f}$ and obtaining the covariances of the polynomial coefficients.</p>\n\n<p>My question is as follows. The random variables $X,Y,\\ldots$ and $\\hat{f}$ are used to estimate a new quantity, $\\hat{Q}\\in\\mathbb{R}$ which is a test statistic of the distribution of $\\hat{f}(X,Y,\\ldots)$ (in fact it is a quantile).</p>\n\n<p>If I had chosen different samples $x_i,y_i,\\ldots$ then I'd end up with a different $\\hat{f}$ and a different $\\hat{Q}$. I would like to calculate the possible effect of estimation error on $\\hat{Q}$ from the uncertainty in estimating the coefficients. </p>\n\n<p>Is this problem as simple as follows? Suppose $\\hat{f}(x,y,\\ldots)=\\hat{\\beta_0}+\\hat{\\beta_1}\\cdot x+\\hat{\\beta_2}\\cdot y+\\hat{\\beta_3}\\cdot xy+\\beta_4 \\cdot x^2+\\cdots$ are the polynomial coefficients. I assume that</p>\n\n<p>$\\beta_i\\sim N(\\hat{\\beta_i},\\hat{\\sigma_i}^2)$</p>\n\n<p>where $\\hat{\\sigma_i}^2$ are the sample covariances from my linear model fit and then I have</p>\n\n<p>$Q\\sim N(\\hat{Q},\\sum\\frac{\\partial\\hat{Q}}{\\partial\\beta_i}\\cdot\\hat{\\sigma_i}^2)$</p>\n\n<p>where the sum is taken over all coefficients of linear terms (so ignoring higher order terms in $\\hat{f}$ like $\\beta_3,\\beta_4$). Happily I know $\\partial\\hat{Q}/\\partial\\beta_i$. Hence a confidence interval.</p>\n\n<p>Is this correct? I'm concerned about ignoring the higher order terms in $\\hat{f}$. Are there alternative approaches eg. bootstrapping? or some references you can point me to?</p>",

	{
		"ReportLink" : "http://chat.meta.stackexchange.com/transcript/message/2934842",
		"PostUrl" : "http://security.stackexchange.com/a/79709",
		"Site" : "security.stackexchange.com",
		"Title" : "You have to differ two things:\n\nA) The hash function as a function to tr...",
		"Body" : "<p>You have to differ two things:</p>\n\n<p><strong>A)</strong> The hash function as a function to transform a given set of information input to a well defined set of output. If you look at this aspect of a hashing function, it has to solve two problems:</p>\n\n<p>1) It should be designed to avoid collisions - it would be a mess, if you have a high collision rate because it would be easier to \"guess\" the password. Think of a  function which sums up every ASCII-Position of every char input: the <em>outcome</em> for \u00BBab\u00AB is the same as for \u00BBba\u00AB. So this would be really a very bad choice.</p>\n\n<p>2) It should be deterministic so that you could reproduce the result. \nHashes are used for comparison. So it should be clear, that a function, which has no deterministic output is useless.</p>\n\n<p><strong>B)</strong> The use of a hashing-algorithm in the context of storing passwords in a database. </p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>How is hashing safe if a given string always generates the same hash?</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>From (A) it is clear, that, since the output is deterministic a possible attack vector would be to use premade/-calculated hashes aka <em>Rainbow-Tables</em>. </p>\n\n<p><em>simple example:</em></p>\n\n<p>Say, your password is \"hello world\". The <em>MD5</em>-Sum is: <em>6f5902ac237024bdd0c176cb93063dc4</em>. \nGoogling (our \u00BB<em>Rainbow table</em>\u00AB for the sake of the example) for that checksum leads you to <a href=\"http://pkgs.fedoraproject.org/lookaside/extras/koji/hello/6f5902ac237024bdd0c176cb93063dc4/\" rel=\"nofollow\">this</a> location, where you find a file, whose content is \"hello world\". So simply hashing isn't enough. A way to improve security is to use a salt (which could be stored alongside the hash). In our case, let's add <em>6f5902ac237024bdd0c176cb93063dc4</em> (the <em>MD5</em>-sum of the previous example) to the passphrase => \u00BB<em>hello world6f5902ac237024bdd0c176cb93063dc4</em>\u00AB. The new MD5 is <em>f59c64e092edb4fbc2904a3b28ce88c5</em>. If you google that, you have no results. </p>\n\n<p>Beware: I am not(!) suggesting, using <em>MD5</em> in this way is in any way \"<em>secure</em>\" - but I used it to exemplify how a salt affects the outcome of a hashing function. Although the hash is calculated deterministically, the output for one password and two different salts is different enough to make the \"<em>guessing</em>\"-part a bit harder.</p>",
		"TimeStamp" : "2015-01-21T10:19:38.997Z",

		"Body" : "<p>I'll start from the beginning:</p>\n\n<ol>\n<li>Check the call for <code>logrotate</code> inside <code>/etc/cron.daily/logrotate</code> to see if some special conf file is used. Traditionally <code>/etc/logrotate.conf</code> is used.</li>\n<li>Inside your <code>.conf</code> file, look for <code>include</code> directive. You should have one: <code>include /etc/logrotate.d</code> and grep this directory for <code>error_log</code>. Also, check that there is no system specific logs declared inside the <code>.conf</code> file.</li>\n</ol>\n\n<p>Have you found anything?</p>",

		"Title" : "Your question is quite unclear. On the wall, there are multiple classes ...",
		"Body" : "<p>Your question is quite unclear. On the wall, there are multiple classes of brothers:\n1-Kind of civilians: Builders, cooks, maesters and assistants. This kind of brothers is not deemed fit to train for arms, and most of the cases, the masters in arms<br>\n2-Soldiers : This is the most common type of brothers on the wall, they are trained to wield a sword and perhaps use a bow and arrow. Their day to day tasks are to mount gards on the wall and engage enemy in defense of the wall.\nNB: the first and second category are very close, and their tasks may be confused, and some sources mention that :</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Every man in the Watch walks the wall, and all are expected to bare steel in its defense, but the rangers are the true fighting men of the Watch (I: 372)</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>However we never heard of Sam Tarly walking the wall. So...</p>\n\n<p>3-Rangers: These are the gifted unfortunate, that have joined the wall for one reason or another. They're hence given the toughest quests. Rangers often dwell behind the wall, and seldom on it. They are generally good trackers and stealth masters. They know very well their way in the land of the far north. Qhorin Halfhand and Benjen Stark are very known rangers.</p>\n\n<p>Regarding the armour now that is the core of your question. The first category doesn't require one, so what they wear around is what keeps them warmest, so any kind of animal fur or skin or leather would do.(I am not taking into consideration the latest events on the wall were resources were scarce and everybody engaged in battle).\nRecruits of the Watch wear often </p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>roughspun black (I: 149)</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>because such described wear is hard to get by and </p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>On the Wall, a man gets only what he earns (I: 150)</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>The second category, is the one destined more for battle. However, they prefer boiled leather to any other protection. The main reason behind that is that steel is cold, and gets colder with the cold of the north, can even cause problems during long watches. \nThe third category, is the rangers'. Well this category even though it seems to be the most danger exposed one, is the least worried about protection, for several reasons. If they go detected on their reckon missions, no kind of armour would save them. If they stay exposed in the cold with heavy armour, they'd die of cold. So they prefer skin. </p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Rangers often share skins for warmth (III: 169)</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/OJkKM.jpg\" alt=\"Qhorin Halfhand by Matt Olson\"></p>\n\n<p>Oh, and of course, all these categories have cloaks of course, black washed out cloaks. \nAnd before I end my answer (which cannot really be considered as answer for lack of details about the question) I have to add that in order to answer this question properly, we need to study the armour of the free folks. They're more exposed to war than the black watch, and they're accustomed to war in cold. Some have bones for armour, some boiled leather, and whatever armour the brothers of the watch use, is either stolen from free folks (it goes the other way around also) either inspired by them. After all, a seasoned brother of the night watch, is very similar to any one of the free folk, I guess the circumstances change a person.</p>\n\n<p>PS: I heavily relied in this answer on this excellent <a href=\"http://www.westeros.org/Citadel/Concordance/Section/3.3./\" rel=\"nofollow\">website</a>.</p>",

		"Body" : "<p>Several resources around the net (apologies for not having links handy) recommend to determine the total amount of available physical memory on a Linux system by the second value on the \"-/+ buffers/cache\" line in the output of <code>free</code>, with the explanation that buffers and cache may be discarded immediately if a process tries to allocate more memory than is unused at the time (\"Mem:\" line of <code>free</code>). I've found this statement to be consistently empirically wrong, meaning allocating more memory than is \"unused\" fails frequently.</p>\n\n<p>Researching about this, I've found the \"MemAvailable:\" line in <code>/proc/meminfo</code>, and <a href=\"https://lkml.org/lkml/2013/11/7/264\" rel=\"nofollow\">this explanation</a>:</p>\n\n<pre><code>Subject: provide estimated available memory in /proc/meminfo\n\nMany load balancing and workload placing programs check /proc/meminfo\nto estimate how much free memory is available. They generally do this\nby adding up \"free\" and \"cached\", which was fine ten years ago, but\nis pretty much guaranteed to be wrong today.\n\nIt is wrong because Cached includes memory that is not freeable as\npage cache, for example shared memory segments, tmpfs, and ramfs,\nand it does not include reclaimable slab memory, which can take up\na large fraction of system memory on mostly idle systems with lots\nof files.\n\nCurrently, the amount of memory that is available for a new workload,\nwithout pushing the system into swap, can be estimated from MemFree,\nActive(file), Inactive(file), and SReclaimable, as well as the \"low\"\nwatermarks from /proc/zoneinfo.\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>My problem is that the system available for me to run my programs on has a 3.2.0 kernel which apparently does not provide \"MemAvailable\".</p>\n\n<p><strong>My question:</strong> How can I (approximately) compute the amount of available physical memory myself, using that memory information that is available to me?</p>\n\n<pre><code>MemTotal:       16536344 kB\nMemFree:         8615224 kB\nBuffers:          241896 kB\nCached:          1341944 kB\nSwapCached:       100232 kB\nActive:          5320768 kB\nInactive:        2021312 kB\nActive(anon):    4298508 kB\nInactive(anon):  1483164 kB\nActive(file):    1022260 kB\nInactive(file):   538148 kB\nUnevictable:          32 kB\nMlocked:              32 kB\nSwapTotal:       9918460 kB\nSwapFree:        7730432 kB\nDirty:                56 kB\nWriteback:             0 kB\nAnonPages:       5720696 kB\nMapped:           103628 kB\nShmem:             23432 kB\nSlab:             432516 kB\nSReclaimable:     356780 kB\nSUnreclaim:        75736 kB\nKernelStack:        7320 kB\nPageTables:        69764 kB\nNFS_Unstable:          0 kB\nBounce:                0 kB\nWritebackTmp:          0 kB\nCommitLimit:    18186632 kB\nCommitted_AS:   12325296 kB\nVmallocTotal:   34359738367 kB\nVmallocUsed:      120924 kB\nVmallocChunk:   34351227352 kB\nHardwareCorrupted:     0 kB\nAnonHugePages:         0 kB\nHugePages_Total:       0\nHugePages_Free:        0\nHugePages_Rsvd:        0\nHugePages_Surp:        0\nHugepagesize:       2048 kB\nDirectMap4k:      103240 kB\nDirectMap2M:    16738304 kB\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>PS: I realize the actual computation is detailed in the kernel patch I linked to, but I'm having a hard time relating this to the output that is available to me.</p>",

		"Body" : "<p>For a web app, the client side is javascript in the browser. The server side is ASP.NET with a REST API. At present there is a single server but we plan to scale out with a server each in the US, UK, and AUS (on Azure). We'll have redis (but that does not sync up instantaneously). They will (almost) always be using SSL.</p>\n\n<p>When a user logs in, we authenticate them. It's easy to pass back the primary key of that user record in the DB and on subsequent calls in, pass that PK to identify the user. It's also trivially easy to then impersonate any user.</p>\n\n<p>What's the best way to implement this? The two things I have thought of are:</p>\n\n<ol>\n<li>Return a guid and require that guid on all subsequent calls.</li>\n<li>Store the PK in the Session data on the server side and use that to identify the user on all subsequent calls.</li>\n</ol>\n\n<p>Both of the above work if an existing session continues to go to the same server (which I believe it does) for each subsequent request.</p>\n\n<p>So, what's the best way to do this? 		"ReportLink" : "http://chat.meta.stackexchange.com/transcript/message/2934711",
		"PostUrl" : "http://serverfault.com/a/653332",
		"Site" : "serverfault.com",
		"Title" : "You asked for ideas and... here is mine.\n\nTo solve your problem, you've ...",
		"Body" : "<p>You asked for ideas and... here is mine.</p>\n\n<p>To solve your problem, you've two very limiting conditions:</p>\n\n<ol>\n<li><p>You're unable to take hands on your Cisco ('cause it's not yours and its configuration cannot be changed to suite your needs);</p></li>\n<li><p>You cannot change (at least, not easily) the way Zeroshell is working (due to the very nature of Zeroshell itself [it's quite complex to rebuild Zeroshell to suite your needs [see below]).</p></li>\n</ol>\n\n<p>On the other end as you want REAL_TIME_MONITORING and PER-PORT-TRAFFIC-ACCOUNTING you're mostly forced to have at least one point (one network interface) where:</p>\n\n<ol start=\"3\">\n<li>All the traffic will be flowing, so for you to \"account\" the all of it;</li>\n<li>the interface is \"owned\" by some equipment you can manage.</li>\n</ol>\n\n<p>What I have done in such situations is to <em>REPLACE</em> the existing appliance (in your case: Zeroshell; in my case various hardware appliances from various vendors) with something I can fully manage without constraints: a common linux box with at least two interfaces properly configured to route/firewall traffic.</p>\n\n<p>Let's suppose this could be OK for you (...even tough I understand that could be an issue, for you, due to the initial setup-efforts).</p>\n\n<p><em>IF</em> such a machine is available, <em>THEN</em> I'd add to the set of software to install on it:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><p><a href=\"http://iptraf.seul.org/\" rel=\"nofollow\">IPTRAF</a>: despite its age, it's still perfectly able to gives out REAL-TIME data from  your network interfaces. It provides a character-user-interface, so it can be launched remotely, within a simple SSH connection (no web, no big GUI libraries, etc.);</p></li>\n<li><p><a href=\"http://www.ntop.org/products/ntop/\" rel=\"nofollow\">NTOP</a>:  from the official website: \"<em>...a network traffic probe that shows the network usage, similar to what the popular top Unix command does...</em>\". NTOP is way much feature-rich than IPTRAF. Definitely more powerful (but more complex to configure/install than a single \"<em>apt-get install</em>\" or \"<em>yum install</em>\")</p></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>As clearly stated, both tools above provides good <strong>REAL-TIME</strong> data (as you asked in your question). Anyway, I'm quite confident that you need <em><strong>ALSO</strong></em> asynchronous data: I'm sure you want also to be able to check something like: \"<em>who were the hosts/MACs that generated/consumed most of the traffic, yesterday? And for which protocols?</em>\", probably drilling down such data back to a single IP/MAC/PORT, and down to a granularity of.... 1 minute. Don't you? In such a case I strongly reccomend:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"http://pmacct.net/\" rel=\"nofollow\">PMACCT</a>: from the official website: \"<em>...pmacct is a small set of passive network monitoring tools to measure, account, classify, aggregate and export IPv4 and IPv6 traffic..</em>\". Please note that PMACCT can solve a wide range of problems, most of them suited for big/large ISP/operators. Nevertheless, it can run perfectly of your linux-box and account for traffic flowing along its interfaces. With a configuration like this:</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>-</p>\n\n<pre><code>host:~# cat /etc/pmacct/pmacctd.conf\n\ninterface: eth0\ndaemonize: true\naggregate: src_mac,dst_mac,src_host,dst_host,proto,src_port,dst_port\n\nports_file: /etc/pmacct/ports.list \n\nplugins: mysql\n\nsql_user: pmacct\nsql_passwd: sqlpassword\nsql_db: pmacct\nsql_table: acct_v4_%Y_%m_%d\n[...]\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>it can easily keep track of traffic flowing along eth0 in a mysql table, so for you to easily check what happened on your network with a common/simple SQL-query.</p>\n\n<p>Just to give you some real numbers, I've succesfully used PMACCT on a server with a XEON X3350; 4GB of RAM; 4 broadcom GigaEth interfaces; nearly 70 VLANs configured on eth0 and pmacct listening on all of them; +/- 300GB of various IP traffic routed on a daily basis; PMACCT generating accounting EVERY_MINUTE, for EVERY_VLAN, for EVERY tuple (src_mac, dst_mac, src_ip, dst_ip, src_port, dst_port); +/- 60.000.000 accounting records per day. \nAll of this, without any issue (but writing on text-files, not in MySQL). In smaller environments, anyway, there are no problems in writing directly to MySQL.</p>\n\n<p>Also, please note that thanks to PMACCT I keep track of <em>EACH</em> IP addresses seen on my networks, on a daily basis (in other words: I know that 10.29.19.89 have not been seen since july 16th 2014; 172.17.1.45 have never been seen [since the start of PMACCT accounting]; etc.).</p>\n\n<p>Also on PMACCT: I have configured the ethernet switch connecting my main Internet-gateway, to \"mirror\" its traffic to a free port, where I've plugged an ad-hoc linux-box accounting all the Internet traffic (a 1GEth link). No issue at all.</p>\n\n<p>A final note about PMACCT: should you (or some other readers) wonder why I <strong>NOT</strong> choosed some more common NETFLOW/IPFIX probe/collector, the reason is very simple: PMACCT is the only one I've found being able to account also MAC-addresses.</p>",

		"Title" : "\n  I was thinking about renting a cluster and I heard about Amazon EC2, ...",
		"Body" : "<blockquote>\n  <p>I was thinking about renting a cluster and I heard about Amazon EC2, but I have no experience with its services and I do not know how to use them.</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>Amazon's AWS has a elaborate documentation, for reference here is the <a href=\"http://aws.amazon.com/documentation/gettingstarted/\" rel=\"nofollow\">Getting Started</a> link to get you going. Also, AWS <a href=\"http://aws.amazon.com/training/self-paced-labs/\" rel=\"nofollow\">self-paced labs</a> are worth checking out.</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>I am in need of 5 machines with the following specifications (for each machine): A dual-processor, 8GB of RAM, and 500GB of disk.</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>Amazon's AWS provides a wide range of EC2 instance types. Choose which one best fits your use-case from a list of <a href=\"http://aws.amazon.com/ec2/instance-types/\" rel=\"nofollow\">instance types</a>.</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>I want to setup the Linux operating system and the Hadoop framework manually, just like I would if I had the machines physically on my hands. I would like to know if Amazon EC2 offers something like this, and I would like to estimate the cost of this infrastructure for, let's say, a month.</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>AWS does not provide a VM without an OS installed in it. All the VM's provided by AWS are pre-loaded with OS and you could manually install Hadoop on top of that. Of course AWS provides a wide range of OS.</p>\n\n<p>Amazon AWS also provides a <a href=\"http://calculator.s3.amazonaws.com/index.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">Simple Monthly Calculator</a> to calculate how much your cluster might cost based on the instances you have selected and number of EB2 volumes you have attached to each instance.</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>In the case I choose Amazon's Elastic MapReduce framework, would I be able to control de version of Hadoop? Could I also be able to change the configuration of the scheduler in it so that I can set my algorithm?</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>If you are using AWS EMR to deploy Hadoop cluster then you could select the version of Hadoop to be installed, supported Hadoop versions by Amazon are 2.4.0, 2.2.0, 1.0.3, 0.20.205.</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Finally, I would like to know if there is any kind of simulator for MapReduce to make different experiments.</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>I did not understand about the mapreduce simulator part though.</p>",

		"Body" : "<p>According to the book <a href=\"http://rads.stackoverflow.com/amzn/click/0321784073\" rel=\"nofollow\">PHP and MySQL for Dynamic Web Sites (4th edition)</a></p>\n\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\n\n<pre><code>$r = mysqli_query($dbc, $q);\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>For simple queries like <strong>INSERT</strong>, <strong>UPDATE</strong>, <strong>DELETE</strong>, etc. (which do not return records), the <code>$r</code> variable\u2014short for result\u2014will be either <strong>TRUE</strong> or <strong>FALSE</strong>, depending upon whether the query executed successfully.</p>\n\n<p>Keep in mind that \u201Cexecuted successfully\u201D means that it ran without error; it\ndoesn\u2019t mean that the query\u2019s execution necessarily had the desired result; you\u2019ll need to test for that.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Then how to test?</strong></p>\n\n<p>While the <code>mysqli_num_rows()</code> function will return the number of rows generated by a <strong>SELECT</strong> query, <code>mysqli_affected_rows()</code> returns the number of rows affected by an <strong>INSERT</strong>, <strong>UPDATE</strong>, or <strong>DELETE</strong> query. It\u2019s used like so:</p>\n\n<pre><code>$num = mysqli_affected_rows($dbc);\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Unlike <code>mysqli_num_rows()</code>, the one argument the function takes is the database connection (<strong>$dbc</strong>), not the results of the previous query (<strong>$r</strong>).</p>",

		"PostUrl" : "http://sharepoint.stackexchange.com/a/129120",
		"Site" : "sharepoint.stackexchange.com",
		"Title" : "With CSR you need the referenced Columns in the view, and OP asked for h...",
		"Body" : "<p>With CSR you need the referenced Columns in the view, and OP asked for hiding those Columns. </p>\n\n<p>With the non-CSR approach below the only Column needed in the View is Status.</p>\n\n<p>And it works in any instance of the View on other pages.. without making JSlink connections </p>\n\n<p>It also works with multiple Views on the same page, again, something CSR has issues with. </p>\n\n<p>CSR is great technology, but not always the best solution. Method below works on SP2010 as well. </p>\n\n<h1>The Javascript code</h1>\n\n<p>Thanks for mailing me your JSlink code. </p>\n\n<p>I rewrote it just a tad so its more modular and easier to work into a SharePoint Calculated Column (which I will post later)</p>\n\n<p>The major change I made was using the dates instead of Port number to check where a ship is. </p>\n\n<p>So the dates array is ETA1 , ETS1 , ETA2 , ETS2 , ...</p>\n\n<p>That saves a whole lot of date comparisons.</p>\n\n<pre><code>/*jslint plusplus:true */\n/*jslint bitwise:true */\n/*global console*/\nfunction ShipStatus(checkdate, ports, dates) {\n    \"use strict\";\n    var i = 0,\n        state = {},\n        lost = false;\n    dates = dates.map(function (S) {\n        return new Date(S);\n    });\n    while (!lost && checkdate > dates[i]) {\n        i++;\n        lost = !dates[i] || dates[i - 1] > dates[i];\n    }\n    state = {\n        'date': checkdate.toDateString(),\n        'status': [['Sailing to:', 'In Port:'], ['Lost at sea', 'Lost in Port']][~~lost][i % 2],\n        'port': ports[~~(i / 2)],\n        'transit': ['Arriving', 'Departing'][i % 2],\n        'nextdate': dates[i].toDateString(),\n        'color': [['#00ffff', '#00ff00'], ['lightcoral', 'red']][~~lost][i % 2]\n    };\n    return (state);\n}\n\nvar ports, dates;\nports = ['[Port 1]', '[Port 2]', '[Port 3]', '[Port 4]', '[Port 5]'];\ndates = ['1/14/2015', '1/19/2015', '1/19/2015', '1/20/2015', '1/21/2015', '1/24/2015', '1/27/2015', '1/27/2015', '1/28/2015', '1/29/2015'];\n\nvar S;\nconsole.clear();\nS = new ShipStatus(new Date(), ports, dates);//todays date\nconsole.log(S.date, S.status, S.port, S.transit, S.nextdate, S.color);\nS = new ShipStatus(new Date('1/22/2015'), ports, dates);\nconsole.log(S.date, S.status, S.port, S.transit, S.nextdate, S.color);\n\n//Now set status text in UI\n//Now set background color in UI\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>You can paste this as a Chrome Snippet and easily test.</p>\n\n<p>Some (dirty) JavaScript tricks..  lost is a boolean which is cast to a 0 or 1 with ~~lost; that way it can be used as in index in array</p>\n\n<p>i % 2 results in an index as well</p>\n\n<p>since each port has 2 dates (ETA and STS) ~~(i/2) gets us the correct index into the ports array</p>\n\n<h1>Now into SharePoint</h1>\n\n<p>Okay; so as discussed today in a private chat, you create 2 extra Calculated Columns: <strong>Posts</strong> and <strong>Dates</strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>Posts</strong> I have hardcoded because I did not want to create all those other columns:</p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.imgur.com/CBZtGoT.png\" alt=\"http://i.imgur.com/CBZtGoT.png\"></p>\n\n<p><strong>Dates</strong> you need to format like a long sequency of</p>\n\n<p>=CHAR(39)&MONTH(ETA1)&\"/\"&DAY(ETA1)&\"/\"&YEAR(ETA1)&CHAR(39)</p>\n\n<p>The outcome needs to be the exact string:</p>\n\n<pre><code>'1/14/2015', '1/19/2015', '1/19/2015', .....\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>This formatting prevents <strong>any</strong> issues with different language setting.</p>\n\n<p>My hardcoded version:</p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.imgur.com/zws6Me3.png\" alt=\"http://i.imgur.com/zws6Me3.png\"></p>\n\n<p>Note: we'll add the [ ] for the Javascript Array notation later</p>\n\n<p>Once you have those two Calculated Columns add the big one... and set this one to datatype=Number so it evaluates the HTML</p>\n\n<pre><code>=\"<div style=\"\"width:250px;\"\">placeholder</div>\"\n&\"<img src=\"\"/_layouts/images/blank.gif\"\" onload=\"\"{\"\n&\"  var i=0,state=[],lost=false,checkdate=new Date(),\"\n&\"  ports=[\" & [Ports] & \"],\"\n&\"  dates=[\" & [Dates] & \"].map(function (S) { return new Date(S); });\"\n&\"  while (!lost && checkdate > dates[i]) {\"\n&\"      i++; lost=!dates[i] || dates[i - 1] > dates[i];\"\n&\"  }\"\n&\"  state=[\"\n&\"      [['Sailing to:', 'In Port:'], ['Lost at sea', 'Lost in Port']][~~lost][i % 2],\"\n&\"      ports[~~(i / 2)],\"\n&\"      ['Arriving', 'Departing'][i % 2],\"\n&\"      dates[i].toDateString()\"\n&\"  ];\"\n&\"this.parentNode.parentNode.parentNode.style.backgroundColor=[['#00ffff', '#00ff00'], ['lightcoral', 'red']][~~lost][i % 2];\"\n&\"this.previousSibling.innerText=state.join(' ');\"\n&\"}\"\">\"\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>I rewrote the script a bit so its shorter to output the textparts from an array 'state'</p>\n\n<p>On my SP Online (with hardcoded Dates and Ports as I didn't want to type that much) it looks like:</p>\n\n<p>As I have the same hardcoded dates for all ships all lines look the same!</p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.imgur.com/QsKNtyz.png\" alt=\"http://i.imgur.com/QsKNtyz.png\"></p>",

	{
		"ReportLink" : "http://chat.meta.stackexchange.com/transcript/message/2932578",
		"PostUrl" : "http://english.stackexchange.com/a/222690",
		"Site" : "english.stackexchange.com",
		"Title" : "As I am a non native speaker I appologize for the indulgence of giving m...",
		"Body" : "<p>As I am a non native speaker I appologize for the indulgence of giving my 2 cents and I warn that my grammatical understanding might be tinted by german synthax. But i think that I am able to help, or atleast point in the right direction. As it was already mentioned you would have to change \"has led\" to \"have led\" in your original quote if you would apply \"and\" instead of \"together with\" and i believe this to be the main issue here. Together with is no \"Linker\", it is a preposition which normally</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>\"My work ethic <em>and</em> belief in my ability <em>have</em> led to progress.</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>This is simply because \"and\" links 2 noun phrases together as the <em>subject</em> of your sentence. It is both, your work ethic AND your belief which led to progress. But still it would be more conventional to say:</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>\"my work ethic(,) together with (my) belief in my ability(,) <em>has</em> led to progress.\"</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>Now, why is that? Quite simple; \"Together\" is an adverb. </p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>We did this together. How have we done this? together</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>Now, i am equal how not a big fan of \"together with\" as it seems awkward. but:\n\"together with\" is no linker. It is a preposition which normally introduces an adverbial phrase. It does not answer the question who is doing something but rather \"how\", \"through what\" or \"wherewith/whomwith\" something is done. As in \"YOU ran a marathon together with 1000 other athlets\". Using \"together with\" in your example would give your work ethics an outstanding role in coomparison to your self-belief, which would only have the sidekick. A perfect example to explain the difference of \"together with\" and \"and\" would be the following example:</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>\"the woman passes a man(,) together with some kids\"</p>\n  \n  <p>\"the woman passes a man and some kids\"</p>\n  \n  <p>Atleast i would udnerstand these two sentences differently; in the first sentence it is not the man who is together with \"some kids\" but the women who passes him (though i am unsure about the requirement  of a comma). to clarify that the man is standing there with some kids you would have to say;</p>\n  \n  <p>\"the woman passes a man, <em>who is</em> together with some kids\"</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>Your believe in your ability becomes a tool rather then an actor should you use \"together with\". let's restructure your sentence to illustrate what this means: </p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>\"Together with my/the belief in my ability, my work ethic has led to progress\"</p>\n  \n  <p>or more clumsy: </p>\n  \n  <p>\"My work ethic has led to progress, together with my believe in my ability\"</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>Let's have a look at some more examples to clarify what i mean</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <blockquote>\n    <p>He <em>is</em> playing (together) with his friends</p>\n    \n    <p>He and his friends <em>are</em> playing (alone in their homes) </p>\n    \n    <p>He and his friends are playing together</p>\n  </blockquote>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>the same goes for \"along with\". T</p>",

		"Title" : "If you are simply looking for an answer as to why your balance wasn't de...",
		"Body" : "<p>If you are simply looking for an answer as to why your balance wasn't decreasing, the answer is that your logic was incorrect.</p>\n\n<pre><code>newBalance = (balance - minPay) + (balance * rate);\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Should be:</p>\n\n<pre><code>newBalance = balance + (balance * rate) - minPay ;\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>You want to add the interest to the current balance, and then subtract whatever the minimum payment is. Running your program with that logic gave me:</p>\n\n<pre><code>Enter credit card balance: 100\nEnter interest rate: .1\n90.1\n80.1901\n70.2702901\n60.340560390099995\n50.4009009504901\n40.45130185144059\n30.49175315329203\n20.522244906445323\n10.542767151351768\n0.5533099185031194\n-9.446136771578377\n-19.455582908349953\n-29.475038491258303\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>You could also work on some better coding practices. For example, you shouldn't instantiate a new instance of the class every loop. Instead, continue to use the same class instance. You should also check to see if the balance is 0, for example the output I got from running your program allowed me to pay into the negatives.</p>\n\n<p>Hope this helps, feel free to ask questions if it doesn't make sense.</p>",

\\pttocm\\posy )\n    }\n\n    \\draw [thick,->] (-4.3,0) -- (4.3,0) node[below] {$x$} ;\n    \\draw [thick,->] (0,-2.3) -- (0,7.2) node[left] {$y$};\n    \\draw [dotted] (-4.3,-2.3) grid (4.3,7.2) ;\n    \\draw [name path=h,thick] plot [smooth] coordinates {(-4,-2)(-3,2)(-2,6)(0,2)\n    (2,-2)(3,4)} ;\n    \\draw (0,0) node [below left] {0} ;\n    \\draw (1,0) node [below] {1} ;\n    \\draw (0,1) node [left] {1} ;\n    \\foreach \\i in {-4,-3,-2,-1,1,2,3,4}\n    { \\draw[very thick] (\\i,0) -- (\\i,-0.15) ; }\n    \\foreach \\i in {-2,-1,1,2,3,4,5}\n    { \\draw[very thick] (0,\\i) -- (-0.15,\\i) ; }\n    \\foreach \\i/\\j in { -4/-2, 3/4 }\n    { \\draw (\\i,\\j) node[fill,circle, inner sep=1pt] {} ; }\n    \\draw (-3,-1) node[xshift=-2mm,yshift=1mm] {${C}_h$} ;\n\n    \\draw [name path=g,thick,red] plot[domain=-4.3:4.3]\n    (\\x,{ -(\\x-2)*2/3 }) ;\n    \\draw [dashed,very thick,red] (2,0) -- (2,-2) -- (0,-2) ;\n    \\draw [name path=eq,red] (-4.3,2) -- (4.3,2) ;\n    \\path [name intersections ={of = h and eq }] ;\n    \\coordinate (A) at (intersection-1) ;\n    \\draw[red,thick] (A) node[draw,circle] {} ;\n    \\draw[red] (A) node[below left] {\\printcoords{A}} ;\n    \\coordinate (B) at (intersection-2) ;\n    \\draw[red,thick] (B) node[draw,circle] {} ;\n    \\draw[red] (B) node[above right] {\\printcoords{B}} ;\n    \\coordinate (C) at (intersection-3) ;\n    \\draw[red,thick] (C) node[draw,circle] {} ;\n    \\draw[red] (C) node[above right] {\\printcoords{C}} ;\n    \\path [name intersections ={of = h and g }] ;\n    \\coordinate (D) at (intersection-1) ;\n    \\draw[red,thick] (D) node[draw,circle] {} ;\n    \\draw[red] (D) node[above right] {\\printcoords{D}} ;\n    \\coordinate (E) at (intersection-2) ;\n    \\draw[red,thick] (E) node[draw,circle] {} ;\n    \\draw[red] (E) node [above right] {\\printcoords{E}} ;\n    \\coordinate (F) at (intersection-3) ;\n    \\draw[red,thick] (F) node[draw,circle] {} ;\n    \\draw[red] (F) node[above right] {\\printcoords{F}} ;\n   \\end{tikzpicture}\n\\end{document}\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>It even handles multiple intersection points, thanks to the intersection library.</p>",

		"Body" : "<p>As it turns out the following are SQL Aliases, this is related to the FieldAPI:</p>\n\n<pre><code>'node' AS field_data_field_description_node_entity_type,\n'node' AS field_data_field_menu_photo_node_entity_type,\n'node' AS field_data_field_price_node_entity_type\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>They are replicated using <code>addExpression</code> they <strong>must be before any <code>conditions</code> and <code>addField</code></strong>. Adding the following to my code above replicates the SQL perfectly:</p>\n\n<pre><code>$query->addExpression(\"'node'\", 'field_data_field_FIELD_NAME_node_entity_type');\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Thanks to @calebtr for the help!</p>",

		"Site" : "sharepoint.stackexchange.com",
		"Title" : "Thanks for mailing me your JSlink code. \n\nI rewrote it just a tad so its...",
		"Body" : "<p>Thanks for mailing me your JSlink code. </p>\n\n<p>I rewrote it just a tad so its more modular and easier to work into a SharePoint Calculated Column (which I will post later)</p>\n\n<p>The major change I made was using the dates instead of Port number to check where a ship is. </p>\n\n<p>So the dates array is ETA1 , ETS1 , ETA2 , ETS2 , ...</p>\n\n<p>That saves a whole lot of date comparisons.</p>\n\n<pre><code>/*jslint plusplus:true */\n/*jslint bitwise:true */\n/*global console*/\nfunction ShipStatus(checkdate, ports, dates) {\n    \"use strict\";\n    var i = 0,\n        state = {},\n        lost = false;\n    dates = dates.map(function (S) {\n        return new Date(S);\n    });\n    while (!lost && checkdate > dates[i]) {\n        i++;\n        lost = !dates[i] || dates[i - 1] > dates[i];\n    }\n    state = {\n        'date': checkdate.toDateString(),\n        'status': [['Sailing to:', 'In Port:'], ['Lost at sea', 'Lost in Port']][~~lost][i % 2],\n        'port': ports[~~(i / 2)],\n        'transit': ['Arriving', 'Departing'][i % 2],\n        'nextdate': dates[i].toDateString(),\n        'color': [['#00ffff', '#00ff00'], ['lightcoral', 'red']][~~lost][i % 2]\n    };\n    return (state);\n}\n\nvar ports, dates;\nports = ['[Port 1]', '[Port 2]', '[Port 3]', '[Port 4]', '[Port 5]'];\ndates = ['1/14/2015', '1/19/2015', '1/19/2015', '1/20/2015', '1/21/2015', '1/24/2015', '1/27/2015', '1/27/2015', '1/28/2015', '1/29/2015'];\n\nvar S;\nconsole.clear();\nS = new ShipStatus(new Date(), ports, dates);//todays date\nconsole.log(S.date, S.status, S.port, S.transit, S.nextdate, S.color);\nS = new ShipStatus(new Date('1/22/2015'), ports, dates);\nconsole.log(S.date, S.status, S.port, S.transit, S.nextdate, S.color);\n\n//Now set status text in UI\n//Now set background color in UI\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>You can paste this as a Chrome Snippet and easily test.</p>\n\n<p>Some (dirty) JavaScript tricks..  lost is a boolean which is cast to a 0 or 1 with ~~lost; that way it can be used as in index in array</p>\n\n<p>i % 2 results in an index as well</p>\n\n<p>since each port has 2 dates (ETA and STS) ~~(i/2) gets us the correct index into the ports array</p>",

		"Title" : "I had the same Problem.\nThank you very much for this Help.\nThe Procedure...",
		"Body" : "<p>I had the same Problem.\nThank you very much for this Help.\nThe Procedures didn\u00B4t work for me, so i changed it and work with a temporary-Table.</p>\n\n<p>CREATE TABLE <code>article_plain_date</code> (\n  <code>article_plain_FK</code> INT(11) NOT NULL,\n  <code>atricle_ID</code> INT(11) DEFAULT NULL,\n  <code>ticket_ID</code> INT(11) DEFAULT NULL,\n  <code>create_date</code> DATETIME DEFAULT NULL,\n  PRIMARY KEY (<code>article_plain_FK</code>)\n) ENGINE=MYISAM DEFAULT CHARSET=utf8 COLLATE=utf8_unicode_ci;</p>\n\n<p>INSERT INTO article_plain_date\nSELECT p.id,a.id,t.id,IF(STR_TO_DATE(MID(body,LOCATE('Date: ',body)+6,25),'%a, %e %M %Y %k:%i:%s'),STR_TO_DATE(MID(body,LOCATE('Date: ',body)+6,25),'%a, %e %M %Y %k:%i:%s'),p.create_time) AS create_date  FROM otrs.article_plain p</p>\n\n<p>JOIN article a ON (p.<code>article_id</code> = a.id)\nJOIN ticket t ON (a.<code>ticket_id</code> = t.id);</p>\n\n<p>UPDATE article_plain p\nJOIN article_plain_date d ON (p.<code>article_id</code> = d.<code>atricle_ID</code>)\nSET p.<code>create_time</code> = d.<code>create_date</code>;</p>\n\n<p>UPDATE article a\nJOIN article_plain_date d ON (a.id = d.<code>atricle_ID</code>)\nSET a.<code>create_time</code> = d.<code>create_date</code>;</p>\n\n<p>UPDATE ticket t\nJOIN article_plain_date d ON (t.id = d.<code>ticket_ID</code>)\nSET t.<code>create_time</code> = d.<code>create_date</code>, t.<code>create_time_unix</code> = UNIX_TIMESTAMP(d.<code>create_date</code>);</p>",

	{
		"ReportLink" : "http://chat.meta.stackexchange.com/transcript/message/2929867",
		"PostUrl" : "http://sharepoint.stackexchange.com/a/129069",
		"Site" : "sharepoint.stackexchange.com",
		"Title" : "After much searching, researching, and fiddling around with every bit of...",
		"Body" : "<p>After much searching, researching, and fiddling around with every bit of navigation I could find, I have to give up on actually achieving what I was looking for (a way to change the links at the top of an Access Web App). I could not find the default.aspx anywhere to make any adjustments to it.</p>\n\n<p>What I did find was an agreeable workaround for my specific situation. I found that in addition to the default.aspx for the app, there is also a built-in \"viewer.aspx\" which has no navigation bar at the top of the app. My workaround was to change the link to my Access App from the top-level site, so that it goes to the viewer.aspx instead of default.aspx. This way there is no direct link to the subsite, and no \"Back to Site\" link for people to click on and get confused. I also turned on the top-level site's Publishing so that I could make my links open in new tabs, so that my users don't have to click back a bunch of times to get back to the top-level site. For my situation, this was the best solution to the problem. I hope that this answer will help others who have a similar struggle where they need unique permissions (and therefore subsites), but also desire unique navigation.</p>\n\n<p>Thanks,\n~Sydney</p>",

		"ReportLink" : "http://chat.meta.stackexchange.com/transcript/message/2929820",
		"PostUrl" : "http://math.stackexchange.com/a/1111989",
		"Site" : "math.stackexchange.com",
		"Title" : "Yeah, thanks. It was quite simple. My solution was to verify the marting...",
		"Body" : "<p>Yeah, thanks. It was quite simple. My solution was to verify the martingality of y(t) following the three conditions:<br>1 \u2013 Measurability Condition. y(t) $\\in$ Ft natural filtration since y(t) is a transformation of Bt which is a Ft-martingale for the probabilistic properties of Brownian Motion.<br></p>\n\n<p>2 \u2013 Integrability Condition,\n$$\nE |e^{2B_t - \\alpha t}| < \\infty \\\\\ne^{-\\alpha t} E | e^{2 B_t} | = e^{-\\alpha t} E | e^{N(0,4t)} | = e^{-\\alpha t} e^{0 + \\frac{1}{2} 4t} = e^{-\\alpha t + 2t} < \\infty\n$$</p>\n\n<p>which is a.s. finite if and only if $\\alpha = 2$.<br></p>\n\n<p>3 \u2013 Martingality Condition using the found $\\alpha = 2$, with s \u2264 t\n$$\nE[e^{2B_t - 2t}| F_s] = e^{-2t}E[e^{2B_t}|F_s] = e^{-2t}E[e^{2(B_t - B_s + B_s}|F_s] = e^{-2t}E[e^{2(B_t - B_s)2B_s} | F_s] = e^{2B_s -2t}E[e^{2(B_t - B_s)} | F_s] = e^{2B_s -2t}E[e^{2(B_t - B_s)}] = e^{2B_s -2t}E[e^{N(0,4(t-s)}] = e^{2B_s -2t}e^{2(t - s)} = e^{2B_s - 2s}\n$$</p>\n\n<p>Then also the measurability condition is proved, so y(t) is a martingale for $\\alpha = 2$.</p>",

	{
		"ReportLink" : "http://chat.meta.stackexchange.com/transcript/message/2929810",
		"PostUrl" : "http://dba.stackexchange.com/a/89705",
		"Site" : "dba.stackexchange.com",
		"Title" : "I had this error, and now I have discovered the source of the problem. I...",
		"Body" : "<p>I had this error, and now I have discovered the source of the problem. I had a hard time finding out, so maybe this will be useful to someone, even though I realize, my problem and workaround may not be spot on matching op's original trouble.</p>\n\n<p>I am migrating data from MSSQL to MySQL, and the content being migrated is html-content from Sitecore CMS (target CMS is Drupal, btw).</p>\n\n<p>I've found, that I get this error when converting the database and hitting records, that contain <strong>Instagram-embeds</strong>. Instagram-embeds work in the way, that the embedded post data is copied to the embed code (instead of being loaded async., et.c. - even the image is included as base64-css...), and the young people nowadays tend to put a lot of emoji's in their image-descriptions (using their iPhones with Emoji keyboard). Emoji's are represented by 4-byte encoded characters, but MySQL <code>utf8</code> only allows for 3-byte encoded unicode characters.</p>\n\n<p>My initial error from running <code>wbcopytables.exe</code> (which is the non-GUI way of doing Migration Wizard in MySQL Workbench) was the</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Error during charset conversion of wstring: No error</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>but upgrading MySQL Workbench to recent version (from <em>5.something</em> to <em>6.x</em>) makes the error a bit more descriptive, hinting table and column (alas, not row):</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>ERROR: Could not successfully convert UCS-2 string to UTF-8 in table\n  [MyDatabase].[dbo].[MyTable] (column MyColumn).\n  Original string: ...</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>Anyway - a solution *could* be to use <code>utf8mb4</code> which would allow for the emoji's. Read more <a href=\"http://stackoverflow.com/questions/10957238/incorrect-string-value-when-trying-to-insert-utf-8-into-mysql-via-jdbc\">here</a>.</p>\n\n<p>But it looks like, it's <a href=\"https://www.drupal.org/node/1314214\" rel=\"nofollow\">a bad idea</a> to do this in e.g. my case with Drupal. </p>\n\n<p>So - the solution I ended up with was simply to strip these characters in my migrate-script. There is no point in keeping these for users of the site in question, since they are being displayed as rectangles on the webpage anyway. Script happens to be c# .NET, and I found the help <a href=\"http://stackoverflow.com/questions/28023682/how-do-i-remove-emoji-characters-from-a-string\">here</a> (thanks a ton, <a href=\"http://stackoverflow.com/users/22656/jon-skeet\">Jon Skeet</a>) - turns out there is a regex-pattern for matching one half of a surrogate pair in UTF-16. See below (and use the pattern in another language if needed).</p>\n\n<pre><code>var emojiStripped = Regex.Replace(stringWithEmojis, @\"\\p{Cs}\", string.Empty);\n</code></pre>",

		"Title" : "You would need to do something like this:\n\ngoogle.maps.event.addListener...",
		"Body" : "<p>You would need to do something like this:</p>\n\n<pre><code>google.maps.event.addListener(marker, 'click', function() {\n    window.location.href = this.url;\n});\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Where <code>marker</code> is the reference to the marker you created (of type <code>google.maps.Marker</code>).</p>\n\n<p>So, updating your code to the following OK oh shit here are these terrible gnome VNC grey screens again .. digging digging through Gnome forums (other vnc servers run happily Linux Mint) then I noted I need to set Vino params over SSH - got \"Cannot autolaunch D-Bus without X11 $DISPLAY\" (I DONT HAVE A DESKTOP!!!), tried the DBUS shell script - that of course doesnt work, then found out (while vnc is already running and I have a 'Display') , I can issue:</p>\n\n<pre><code>DISPLAY=:1 gsettings set org.gnome.Vino require-encryption false\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>yes that executes without an error\n(display number is your vnc desktop number)\nbut still that shit grey screen in the vnc terminal...</p>\n\n<p>So again, January 2015, the setting of variables through SSH so that a VNC client will efficiently work on GNOME is still a disaster and the advice stands firm to leave GNOME and install XFCE as above. 	{
		"ReportLink" : "http://chat.meta.stackexchange.com/transcript/message/2929429",
		"PostUrl" : "http://stackoverflow.com/a/28045075",
		"Site" : "stackoverflow.com",
		"Title" : "Trying to answer you question I decided to create HOWTO from the very be...",
		"Body" : "<p>Trying to answer you question I decided to create HOWTO from the very beginning what I did to get my Drool rules executed on remote server. </p>\n\n<p>My task was to integrate Kie Workbench and Execution Server, so business users be able to create Drools rules and deploy them to the Repo, while developers could use these rules via calling REST services of standalone Drools execution server. </p>\n\n<p>You should follow these steps:</p>\n\n<p><strong>Before using Drools Execution Server let me use such terminology:</strong></p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Kie Drools Workbench - is UI for creating and deploying Model and\nRules file(s) to Maven Repository</li>\n<li>Kie Execution Server - is standalone Drools execution server. It consumes REST calls of commands and returns execution results</li>\n<li>Assumed you have Tomcat 7.0/8.0 and Maven installed</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><strong>Deployment of Drools Workbench</strong></p>\n\n<p>Most stable version of  Kie Drools Workbench to deploy at the moment is  6.1.0.Final. Use this one for deploying on Tomcat 7.0 only!</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><p>You can download file called kie-drools-wb-distribution-wars from <a href=\"https://repository.jboss.org/nexus/index.html#nexus-search;gav~~kie-drools-wb-distribution-wars~~~\" rel=\"nofollow\">Jboss sonar repo</a>, use version 6.1.0.Final and <strong>tomcat7.war</strong></p></li>\n<li><p>Make sure you added following jars to Tomcat's lib directory: <strong>javax.security.jacc-api-1.4.jar, kie-tomcat-integration.jar, slf4j-api-1.7.2.jar</strong></p></li>\n<li><p>Make sure you have or added following roles/users to tomcat-users.xml of your Tomcat:</p></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p></p><div class=\"snippet\" data-lang=\"js\" data-hide=\"false\">\n<div class=\"snippet-code\">\n<pre class=\"snippet-code-html lang-html prettyprint-override\"><code><role rolename=\"admin\"/> <!-- Tomcat Admin role -->\n<role rolename=\"analyst\"/> <!-- Kie Workbench Analyst role. -->\n<role rolename=\"kie-server\"/> <!-- Kie Drools Execution Server role. Needed to make REST Rules execution request -->\n<user username=\"admin\" password=\"admin\" roles=\"manager-gui,manager-script\" /> <!-- Tomcat Admin user -->\n<user username=\"user1\" password=\"user1\" roles=\"admin, kie-server\" /> <!-- Kie Drools Execution Server user. Needed to make REST Rules execution request --></code></pre>\n</div>\n</div>\n<p></p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Deploy tomcat7.war to Tomcat. I'm sure you know how to make it </li>\n<li>Open link: <a href=\"http://localhost:8080/kie-drools-wb-distribution-wars-6.1.0.Final-tomcat7.0/\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://localhost:8080/kie-drools-wb-distribution-wars-6.1.0.Final-tomcat7.0/</a>. Use admin credentials configured in previous step to enter Workbench. In our case <strong>user1/user1</strong></li>\n<li><p>In Kie Workbench create a Model, Rules file. Validate them and click Deploy. Make sure you have jar file with your project being put to Maven repo!</p>\n\n<p>As an example you can use rule and model I created for testing purposes:\nDrool rule file:</p>\n\n<pre><code>import com.arty.drlwb.MyExampleType;\n\nrule \"one\"\nwhen \nMyExampleType(message == \"Hello Worlddddd\")\nthen\nSystem.out.println(\"Hello World:)\");\nend\n</code></pre></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><strong>Deployment of Kie Drools Execution Server</strong> </p>\n\n<p>For the moment of this To-Do writing the most stable version of Kie Drools Execution Server is <strong>kie-server-services-6.2.0.Beta3.war</strong>. You can download it here, <a href=\"https://repository.jboss.org/nexus/index.html#nexus-search;gav~org.kie~kie-server-services~~~\" rel=\"nofollow\">Jboss sonar repo</a>: </p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Deploy <strong>kie-server-services-6.2.0.Beta3.war</strong> on Tomcat</li>\n<li>Make GET request on <a href=\"http://localhost:8080/kie-server-services-6.2.0.Beta3/services/rest/server/\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://localhost:8080/kie-server-services-6.2.0.Beta3/services/rest/server/</a>. If you asked to provide user/password use one you've configured for <strong>kie-server role</strong> in <strong>tomcat-users.xml</strong>. You should see same response:   </li>\n</ul>\n\n<p></p><div class=\"snippet\" data-lang=\"js\" data-hide=\"false\">\n<div class=\"snippet-code\">\n<pre class=\"snippet-code-html lang-html prettyprint-override\"><code>    <response type=\"SUCCESS\" msg=\"Kie Server info\">\n      <kie-server-info>\n      <version>6.2.0.Beta3</version>\n      </kie-server-info>\n    </response></code></pre>\n</div>\n</div>\n<p></p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>If you see the same result as I see, now its time to deploy kie container:\nMake PUT request at  <a href=\"http://localhost:8080/kie-server-services-6.2.0.Beta3/services/rest/server/containers/\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://localhost:8080/kie-server-services-6.2.0.Beta3/services/rest/server/containers/</a>{your_container_id}\nUse this XML format:</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p></p><div class=\"snippet\" data-lang=\"js\" data-hide=\"false\">\n<div class=\"snippet-code\">\n<pre class=\"snippet-code-html lang-html prettyprint-override\"><code><kie-container>\n       <container-id>{your_container_id}</container-id>\n       <status/> \n       <release-id>\n            <group-id>{your_project_group_id}</group-id>\n            <artifact-id>{your_project_artifact_id}</artifact-id>\n            <version>{your_project_version}</version>\n      </release-id>\n     <resolved-release-id/>\n</kie-container></code></pre>\n</div>\n</div>\n<p></p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>If you get SUCCESS status response you can check now all containers have been deployed. Make GET on <a href=\"http://localhost:8080/kie-server-services-6.2.0.Beta3/services/rest/server/containers\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://localhost:8080/kie-server-services-6.2.0.Beta3/services/rest/server/containers</a>. You should see your container been deployed:</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p></p><div class=\"snippet\" data-lang=\"js\" data-hide=\"false\">\n<div class=\"snippet-code\">\n<pre class=\"snippet-code-html lang-html prettyprint-override\"><code><response type=\"SUCCESS\" msg=\"List of created containers\">\n <kie-containers>\n <kie-container container-id=\"{your_container_id}\" status=\"STARTED\">\n <release-id>\n<artifact-id>{your_project_artifact_id}</artifact-id>\n<group-id>{your_project_group_id}</group-id>\n<version>{your_project_version}</version>\n</release-id>\n <resolved-release-id>\n<artifact-id>{your_project_artifact_id}</artifact-id>\n<group-id>{your_project_group_id}</group-id>\n<version>{your_project_version}</version>\n</resolved-release-id>\n</kie-container>\n</kie-containers>\n</response></code></pre>\n</div>\n</div>\n<p></p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Now launch all rules you've created and put to your project jar: Make POST request at  <a href=\"http://localhost:8080/kie-server-services-6.2.0.Beta3/services/rest/server/containers/\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://localhost:8080/kie-server-services-6.2.0.Beta3/services/rest/server/containers/</a>{your_container_id}</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Use XML format. of cause use your own model instead of MyExampleType: </p>\n\n<p></p><div class=\"snippet\" data-lang=\"js\" data-hide=\"false\">\n<div class=\"snippet-code\">\n<pre class=\"snippet-code-html lang-html prettyprint-override\"><code><batch-execution lookup=\"defaultKieSession\">\n<insert out-identifier=\"message\" return-object=\"true\" entry-point=\"DEFAULT\">\n    <com.arty.drlwb.MyExampleType>\n          <message>Hello Worlddddd</message>\n    </com.arty.drlwb.MyExampleType>\n</insert>\n<fire-all-rules/>\n</batch-execution></code></pre>\n</div>\n</div>\n<p></p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Check your Tomcat console. If you get <strong>Hello World:)</strong> message and SUCCESS response type all works for you now!</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><strong>P.S</strong> Due to luck of documentation about the topic I checked out Server's sources from <a href=\"https://github.com/droolsjbpm/droolsjbpm-integration/tree/master/kie-server\" rel=\"nofollow\">GitHub</a>. Take a look at <strong>kie-serve-client</strong> and <strong>kie-server-integ-tests</strong> code and tests. Hope this helps.</p>",

user.</p>\n\n<p>I've read several game-related articles regarding game loop, time step, etc and I <em>do</em> understand what's going on, but cannot spot the bug.</p>\n\n<p>What I do: perform scene updates with fixed UPDATE_STEP value (it then gets used when calculating, for example, the Player's new position, being applied to the velocity, etc).\nThen I use the remained slice of time since the last update divided by UPDATE_STEP as a ratio (0..1) to perform the interpolation during rendering.</p>\n\n<p>Basically I change the position of my Player and calibrate the Camera accordingly, all the rest of the game scene (tile map represented as a vertex array) remains untouched.</p>\n\n<p>Could you help me to figure out where's my mistake?\nHere we go:</p>\n\n<pre><code>void gameLoop() {\n\n    const sf::Time UPDATE_STEP = sf::seconds(1.0f / 120.0f);\n    sf::Time timeSinceLastUpdate = sf::Time::Zero;\n    _renderWindow.setFramerateLimit(60);\n    sf::Clock clock;\n\n    while (_renderWindow.isOpen()) {\n\n        sf::Event event;\n        while (_renderWindow.pollEvent(event)) {\n\n            _curGameScene->processEvent(event);\n\n            switch (event.type) {\n break;                \n                default:\n                    break;\n                }\n                break;\n            case sf::Event::Closed:\n                _renderWindow.close();\n timeSinceLastUpdate += dt;\n\n        if (timeSinceLastUpdate > sf::seconds(0.25)) {\n            timeSinceLastUpdate = sf::seconds(0.25);\n        }\n\n        while (timeSinceLastUpdate >= UPDATE_STEP) {\n\n            _curGameScene->update(UPDATE_STEP.asSeconds());\n            timeSinceLastUpdate -= UPDATE_STEP;\n        }\n\n        //RATIO FOR INTERPOLATION DURING RENDER\n        const float alpha = timeSinceLastUpdate.asSeconds() / UPDATE_STEP.asSeconds();\n\n        //normal draw\n        _renderWindow.setView(_renderWindow.getDefaultView());\n        _curGameScene->render(_renderWindow, sf::RenderStates::Default, alpha);\n\n        //ortho draw\n        _renderWindow.setView(_renderWindow.getDefaultView());\n        _renderWindow.draw(infoText);\n        _curGameScene->renderOrtho(_renderWindow);\n\n        _renderWindow.display();\n    }\n}\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>my _curGameScene has the player sprite entity, the camera, which follows him, and \n}\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>player's update method is as follows:</p>\n\n<pre><code>virtual void update(float dtExpandedInSeconds) {\n\n    //store the previous position of the sprite\n    _prevPos = _pos;\n\n    //calculate the new position of the sprite\n    _pos.x = _pos.x + _vxy.x*dtExpandedInSeconds;\n}\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>then when we invoke the LevelScene's render RATIO\n    const sf::Vector2f viewCenter = _camera->calcPos(ratio);\n\n    sf::View view = target.getView();\n    view.setCenter(viewCenter);\n    target.setView(view);\n    target.clear(_bgColor);\n\n    _tileMap->render(target, renderStates, ratio);\n    _player->render(target, renderStates, ratio);\n}\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>which involves the Camera's calcPos //HERE COMES THE INTERPOLATION\n    _calcPos.x = followPrevPos.x*ratio + followPos.x*(1.0-ratio);\n    _calcPos.y = followPrevPos.y*ratio + followPos.y*(1.0-ratio);\n\n    if (_calcPos.x <= _halfViewWH.x) {\n        _calcPos.x = 0;\n    } else if (_calcPos.x <= _mapWH.x - _halfViewWH.x) {\n        _calcPos.x = _calcPos.x - _halfViewWH.x;\n    } else {\n        _calcPos.x = _mapWH.x - _viewWH.x;\n    }\n\n    if (_calcPos.y <= _halfViewWH.y) {\n        _calcPos.y = 0;\n    } else if (_calcPos.y <= _mapWH.y - _halfViewWH.y) {\n        _calcPos.y = _calcPos.y - _halfViewWH.y;\n    } else {\n        _calcPos.y = _mapWH.y - _viewWH.y;\n    }\n\n    _calcPos.x += _halfViewWH.x;\n    _calcPos.y += _halfViewWH.y;\n\n    return _calcPos;\n}\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>The Player's render 		"Title" : "In context that sentence is apparently offensive for two reasons other t...",
		"Body" : "<p>In context that sentence is apparently offensive for two reasons other than use of the word \"<em>n\u00E8gres</em>\":</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>\"According to the Pope in Paris: the French are as stupid as negros\" is literally racist because it implies that all negros are alike, i.e. are all equally \"con\" (and by extension it's also being equally rude about the French; and rude about the Pope, by imputing that quote to him)</li>\n<li>The adjective \"con\" <a href=\"http://www.larousse.fr/dictionnaires/francais-anglais/con/17722\" rel=\"nofollow\">probably means stupid</a>; and/or it might mean \"irritating\" but one thing for sure is that it's not complimentary</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Out of context IMO the literal meaning of \"<em>n\u00E8gre</em>\" is more like \"negro\" than \"nigger\".</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://www.larousse.fr/dictionnaires/francais/n%C3%A8gre/54086\" rel=\"nofollow\">Larousse (the dictionary) says</a>,</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Qui appartient aux Noirs, \u00E0 la culture des Noirs : Musique n\u00E8gre.\n  Populaire.</p>\n  \n  <p>(Terme injurieux et raciste vieilli) Se disait de quelqu'un, d'un groupe de personnes de couleur noire : Tribus n\u00E8gres.</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>I understand/translate that as saying:</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <ul>\n  <li><p>It's primary meaning is Negro or Black, belonging to Black/Negro culture: e.g. <em>negro music</em>. Popular.</p></li>\n  <li><p>(It used to be offensive, it's old-fashioned racist, it's an obsolete term) Was said of someone or of a group of people of black color: e.g. <em>negro tribes</em></p></li>\n  </ul>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>However Google Translate translates \"negro\" as \"<em>noir</em>\" and \"nigger\" as \"<em>n\u00E8gre</em>\" so maybe \"<em>n\u00E8gre</em>\" is more offensive (e.g. closer to \"nigger\" than \"negro\") than I thought. It might be difficult to make an exact comparison/distinction because the history of racism (racist attitude / speech / actions) is not exactly the same in the French-speaking world as in the English.</p>\n\n<p>In the context of \"<em>... aussi cons que ...</em>\" I assume it's <em>trying</em> to be as 'offensive' as possible.</p>",

		"PostUrl" : "http://stats.stackexchange.com/questions/134157",
		"Site" : "stats.stackexchange.com",
		"Title" : "Bit Error Rate - Multiple Bernoulli trials with different probabilities",
		"Body" : "<p>If you transmit a sequence of bits over some line, errors may creep in. For instance, if the Bit Error Rate of this line is 1%, on average, every 1 out of 100 bits will flip to the opposite value.</p>\n\n<p>For a single transmitted bit, this relates to a Bernoulli trial with $p=0.99$ for being a 'success' and $q=1-p=0.01$ for a failure.</p>\n\n<p>If this same bit is transmitted over two identical lines, there are two pathways of getting a correct result: two correct transmissions or two wrong transmissions (flipping the bit twice). The probability, therefore, is $p*p+q*q$.</p>\n\n<p>Following this sequence for multiple transmissions, we get:</p>\n\n<p>$$\n\\begin{array}{r\u00A6c\u00A6c}\n\\textbf{ }&\\textbf{correct}&\\textbf{wrong}\\\\\n\\textbf{1}&p&q\\\\\n\\textbf{2}&p^{2}+q^{2}&2pq\\\\\n\\textbf{3}&p^{3}+3pq^{2}&3p^{2}q+3pq^{2}\\\\\n\\textbf{4}&p^{4}+6p^{2}q^{2}+q^{4}&4p^{3}q+4pq^{3}\n\\end{array}\n$$</p>\n\n<p>The parameters in front of each term seem to relate to Pascal's triangle. Furthemore, the 'correct' descriptions seem to be 'symmetric', while the 'wrong' ones are 'anti-symmetric'. Can somebody explain the connection, and is there perhaps a general function which describes this series?</p>\n\n<p>My real question is the following: what if the bits are transmitted across different lines $i$ each with a different BER $p_i$. The table then becomes:</p>\n\n<p>$$\n\\begin{array}{r\u00A6c\u00A6c}\n\\textbf{ }&\\textbf{correct}&\\textbf{wrong}\\\\\n\\textbf{1}&p_{1}&1-p_{1}\\\\\n\\textbf{2}&2p_{1}p_{2}-p_{1}-p_{2}+1&p_{1}-2p_{1}p_{2}+p_{2}\\\\\n\\textbf{3}&4p_{1}p_{2}p_{3}-2p_{1}p_{2}-2p_{2}p_{3}-2p_{3}p_{1}+p_{1}+p_{2}+p_{3}&etc.\n\\end{array}\n$$</p>\n\n<p>Is there a general function which describes this behaviour? Can someone explain anything more about this series? Does this have a name?</p>",

		"Title" : "I have a similar issue after upgrading to Ubuntu 14.04, which includes A...",
		"Body" : "<p>I have a similar issue after upgrading to Ubuntu 14.04, which includes Apache 2.4.7. </p>\n\n<p>Here is my <strong>workaround</strong>. <em>Emulate</em> <code>mod_dir</code> with <code>mod_rewrite</code>, and disable <code>DirectoryIndex</code>.</p>\n\n<pre><code>#DirectoryIndex index.html index.php index.htm\nDirectoryIndex disabled\n\nRewriteCond %{REQUEST_FILENAME} -d\nRewriteCond %{REQUEST_FILENAME} /$\nRewriteCond %{REQUEST_FILENAME}index.html -f\nRewriteRule ^(.*)$ $1index.html  [L]\n\nRewriteCond %{REQUEST_FILENAME} -d\nRewriteCond %{REQUEST_FILENAME} /$\nRewriteCond %{REQUEST_FILENAME}index.php -f\nRewriteRule ^(.*)$ $1index.php  [L]\n\nRewriteCond %{REQUEST_FILENAME} -d\nRewriteCond %{REQUEST_FILENAME} /$\nRewriteCond %{REQUEST_FILENAME}index.htm -f\nRewriteRule ^(.*)$ $1index.htm  [L]\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Hope this helps.</p>\n\n<hr>\n\n<p><strong>UPDATE</strong>: Upgrading to Apache 2.4.10 fix the issue for me.</p>\n\n<p>Thanks to <a href=\"https://launchpad.net/~ondrej/+archive/ubuntu/apache2\" rel=\"nofollow\">Ond\u0159ej Sur\u00FD</a> this can be done easily on Ubuntu 14.04 with apt:</p>\n\n<pre><code>add-apt-repository ppa:ondrej/apache2\napt-get update\napt-get install apache2\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>p.s. OP confirmed this is fixed in Apache 2.4.9 too.</p>",
