	{
		"ReportLink" : "http://chat.meta.stackexchange.com/transcript/message/2928971",
		"PostUrl" : "http://codegolf.stackexchange.com/questions/44711",
		"Site" : "codegolf.stackexchange.com",
		"Title" : "All those duplicate questions deserve duplicate code to show them off",
		"Body" : "<p>All those questions that are duplicates... Ignored and marginalized by society. It is just not... right. We have to do something. There surely must be love for them too.</p>\n\n<p>They feel appreciated if a piece of code outputs a link to a duplicate question. But the duplicate questions are not so easily impressed. They are swept out off their feet only when the code when duplicated outputs a link to another duplicate question. The more the code can be duplicated and still output these links, the more the questions feel more loved.</p>\n\n<p>Your task is to bring love and appreciation to these Stack Exchange pariahs.</p>\n\n<hr>\n\n<p>Create a piece of code that when duplicated <code>k</code> times outputs a link to a duplicate question. <code>k</code> represents all the numbers in range <code>[1, N]</code>.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Edit</strong> I made this a <strong>code-golf</strong> because I realized you can write a program that can output as many links as you wanted.</p>\n\n<h1>Rules:</h1>\n\n<p><strong>Language:</strong></p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>any language created prior to the post of this challenge is accepted. You may use a language already used in another answer.</li>\n<li>you may <strong>not</strong> use external resources (a database etc.)</li>\n<li><del>any encoding and</del> any characters are allowed (including white spaces, new lines, non-ASCII). <del>Encoding is UTF-8.</del></li>\n<li><del>code size does not matter</del>. Size is measured in bytes.</li>\n<li>all duplications must be in the same language</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><strong>Code duplication:</strong></p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong><em>clarification:</em></strong> the code must not duplicate itself. Simply put duplicating here means creating another code by copy-pasting the original one at the end of the last one obtained. Each will result in a new code that is run independently from the others.</li>\n<li>all the characters in the original code must be copy-pasted (including trailing new line (if any)). Each time the code pasted must be appended at the end.</li>\n<li>the code must create valid output when duplicated <code>1 (no duplication), 2, 3, 4, 5... N times</code>.</li>\n<li>It cannot skip a number (e.g. a code that creates valid output only when duplicated <code>1, 2, 3, 5, 6 times</code> will be considered only for <code>1, 2, 3</code> so <code>N = 3</code>)</li>\n<li>each time exactly one link must be output-ed.</li>\n<li>example (for what duplication means, not for valid output)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>(python3) Original code (k = 1):</p>\n\n<pre><code>try:\n  i\nexcept NameError:\n  i = 100\nelse:\n  i = 200\n\nif i == 100:\n  print(\"stackoverflow.com/questions/\" + str(i),end=\"\")\nelse:\n  print(i)\n</code></pre>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>k = 1 outputs stackoverflow.com/questions/100<br>\n  k = 2 outputs stackoverflow.com/questions/100200<br>\n  k = 3 outputs stackoverflow.com/questions/100200200  </p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p><strong>Duplicate questions links (valid output):</strong></p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Non-deleted questions from <a href=\"http://codegolf.stackexchange.com/\">Programming Puzzles & Code Golf</a> and <a href=\"http://stackoverflow.com/\">Stack Overflow</a> that were closed as duplicate prior to the time of the posting of this post are considered for this challenge.</li>\n<li>Helpful query to search for duplicate questions:</li>\n</ul>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>is:question duplicate:yes</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://codegolf.stackexchange.com/search?q=is%3Aquestion%20duplicate%3Ayes\">duplicates on PPCG</a> and <a href=\"http://stackoverflow.com/search?q=is%3Aquestion%20duplicate%3Ayes\">duplicates on SO</a></p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><p>Link format. Lets take as an example this post:</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://stackoverflow.com/questions/1066589/iterate-through-a-hashmap\">http://stackoverflow.com/questions/1066589/iterate-through-a-hashmap</a></p></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>A valid link output for this question is any of these the two base links</p>\n\n<pre><code>stackoverflow.com/questions/1066589\nstackoverflow.com/q/1066589\n                    ^~~~~~^\n                    this is referred as the link numbere in following paragraphs\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>to which you may add the prefix(es) <code>www.</code> and/or <code>http://</code>. You may also add a trailing <code>/</code></p>\n\n<p>Please note that after that you must not add anything (like the question title), even if that link results in a redirect to the question.</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>You may not use a URL shortner service.</li>\n<li>You may not link to an answer or to another part of the page.</li>\n<li>The questions don't have to be duplicates of the same original or related in any way (<code>don't have to</code> means they can be if you want).</li>\n<li>For each time (for each <code>k</code>) a different question must be linked (two different links to the same question count as the same question)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><strong>Multiple Submissions</strong></p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>You may post multiple answers with the same or different languages. Different posts can output the same link.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h1>Scoring</h1>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Each link gives <strong>1 point</strong>.</li>\n<li><strong>Egoistic bonus</strong>: <strong>+0.5 points</strong> for each link to your own question.</li>\n<li><strong>Forgive me bonus</strong>: <strong>+0.5 point</strong> for each link to a question you voted to close (for whatever reason).</li>\n<li><strong>Judge Jury Executioner bonus</strong>: <strong>+0.5 point</strong> for each link to your own question that you yourself voted to close (for whatever reason). </li>\n<li><strong>now what bonus</strong>: <strong>+0.5 points</strong> for each link to a question closed as a duplicate to a question that has no answers.</li>\n<li><strong>train of thought bonus</strong>: <strong>+1 point</strong> for each link to a question closed as a duplicate to another duplicate question  (regardless of the length of the train)</li>\n<li><strong>dead end bonus</strong>: <strong>+1 point</strong> for each link to a question closed as a duplicate of a question that was closed for a reason other than duplicate. (locked questions that exists because they have historical significance also don't count for this bonus).</li>\n<li><strong>George Santayana bonus</strong>: <strong>+1 point</strong> for each link closed as a duplicate of a question by the same user.</li>\n<li><strong>You can't live without me bonus</strong>: <strong>+1.5 points</strong> for each link whose number is prime.</li>\n<li><strong>Queen of the prom bonus</strong>: <strong>+2 points</strong> for a link to a question of a user with all the questions (on the site of the linked question: PPCG or SO) closed as duplicates (at least 3, including the linked one). This bonus cannot be awarded more than once per user (even if you link to all 3 questions of this user, you are awarded the bonus only once, but you can be awarded this bonus again for a link to a question of another user or the same user but on the other site).</li>\n<li>All bonuses are cumulative. (this for instance has the effect that the <em>Judge Jury Executioner bonus</em> will always come with the <em>egoistic</em> and <em>forgive me</em> bonuses).</li>\n<li><strong>You don't love me enough penalty</strong>:\n<ul>\n<li><code>not_enough_penalty = 0.6</code> for <code>N = 2</code> (just 2 links)</li>\n<li><code>not_enough_penalty = 0.8</code> for <code>N = 3</code> (just 3 links)</li>\n<li><code>not_enough_penalty = 1</code> for <code>N >= 4</code> (4 or more links)</li>\n</ul></li>\n</ul>\n\n<h1><strong>Winning Criteria</strong>:</h1>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>LinkPoints = 1 + bonuses</code> for each link</li>\n<li><strong>Points</strong> = Sum(LinkPoints) * not_enough_penalty</li>\n<li>Votes = number of votes (upvotes - downvotes). Can be negative.</li>\n<li><del><strong>Score</strong> = 5 * Points + Votes</del></li>\n<li><strong>Size</strong> = number of bytes of original code (k = 1).</li>\n<li><p><strong>Score</strong> = (256-Size) / 32 * Points + Votes</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>The winner</strong> is the answer with the highest score. For this, we need to assume a few things:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>You are close to him to be able to capture his traffic, or proble signal;</li>\n<li>He was not using some powerful antenna to strong his signal;</li>\n<li>He didn't change his MAC Address to a fake one;</li>\n<li>He has a wireless network nearby (again, lets pretend he is one of your neighbor);</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Then, you use <strong>airodump-ng</strong> to capture all clients connected to nearby networks, if you are lucky enough it will show his mac address and the wireless network he is connected.</p>\n\n<p><strong>I found his network, so what?</strong></p>\n\n<p>Well, in the past with the network bssid you could find the exactly lagitude and longitude, today there are some database's that still have this information.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Recommendations</strong>:\nProtect your Wireless conection with <strong>WPA2</strong> and use a <strong>strong password</strong> (>32), even if you use WPA2 and put a stupid password, people will break the password by capturing a WPA2 handshake from your network and brute force it.</p>",

	{
		"ReportLink" : "http://chat.meta.stackexchange.com/transcript/message/2923111",
		"PostUrl" : "http://rpg.stackexchange.com/a/55579",
		"Site" : "rpg.stackexchange.com",
		"Title" : "The DMG has a great example of how to change classes into something enti...",
		"Body" : "<p>The DMG has a great example of how to change classes into something entirely new without actually destroying the game balance. It says one of the easier ways of \"making a new class\" is to change the spell list. In that way, the power level of the class isn't altered but it does feel different (it exemplifies the use of a Paladin to make a guardian, using arcane magic to protect a powerful sorcerer instead of divine magic to keep his Oath).</p>\n\n<p>So, here is my suggestion of how you're supposed to do it:</p>\n\n<h2>First Suggestion: Changing the traits of a Wizard and turning it into a Invoker:</h2>\n\n<ol>\n<li><p><strong>Use the wizard as baseline.</strong></p>\n\n<p>If your DM finds it's necessary, change the spellcasting ability to WIS as it was in D&D4e. What you will need to do is to take the Wizard Spell List and change it to make it feel the closest you can get to your old Invoker. Get every destructive spell that reminds you of your encounter and daily powers and eliminate things your invoker certainly wouldn't do (as raising undead).</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Intuitive Magic</strong></p>\n\n<p>Change the trait of spells know. The Invoker is sort of a divine sorcerer. Therefore, it should feel that much as a wizard. I believe this class shouldn't be able to prepare spells and have potentially ilimited number of spells known, but it should work just like the sorcerer, having a number of spells to use according to the sorcerer's spell-list. You'll be sacrificing all the wizard's malleability for one extra cantrip and certainty that you'll always get new spells when you level up.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Change the spell foci</strong></p>\n\n<p>Just do it the same way it was with your Invoker Implements. Wizards use wands and crystal balls (I believe), you invoker though, will go for Rods and Staffs only, just like in 4e.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Choose the school of magic</strong></p>\n\n<p>As a DM, I'd limit it into something that would make it feel like you're using divine intuitive magic. Abjuration, evocation and divination are the ones I'd recommend for that matter.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Ritual caster feature</strong></p>\n\n<p>Invokers are supposed to be ritual casters. You already lost you ability to prepare magic. I'd rule that you'd start with one ritual known and everytime you learn new spells, you get to choose a new ritual. You still know less spells than the wizard that way and you get to keep a cool feature.</p></li>\n</ol>\n\n<p>I'm pretty sure those changes won't affect the power of your class and it's all made according to the DMG suggestions of how to change a class. If you change a few features and keep all the rest as suggested, it won't feel as a wizard nor as a sorcerer. Specially with your unique spell list.</p>\n\n<p>If you dislike it, there's a second simpler option that I dislike but it can work for you. </p>\n\n<h2>Reskin the sorcerer.</h2>\n\n<p>This is quite simple. Just change the description of your character. Sorcerers have great mechanics now that makes them feel like intuitive spell casters (sorcery points).</p>\n\n<p>And if you choose draconic magic, you can always say it's not draconic at all. If you get your dragon wings, you can describe it as angelical wings or wings of light. In the end it's a game about imagining it all anyways.</p>\n\n<p>I hope it was helpful.</p>",

		"Body" : "<p>All of us here know that we just love computer science! Some may like back-end computation because they love scalability for the masses. He or she may be working with some beautiful parallax design in web development. Or messing around with sockets in server design.</p>\n\n<p>Find a project that you'd like to start whether big or small. It's one of the best ways to gain mastery not only in a certain programming language, but, computer science itself.</p>\n\n<p>Screw the academic programming. One may learn about data structures, but he or she has never imagined a useful implementation for them. What can set you apart from \"those that just learn the basics\" is how you apply your knowledge. </p>\n\n<p>Instead of counting the words in a book, how about we count the occurrences of words in a collection of customer reviews about a certain product? 		"Body" : "<p>If I find an NP Hard problem that is equivalent to my problem with an additional constraint, can I still prove that my problem is NP Hard?</p>\n\n<p>Generally, this is probably not the case. For example, the NP Hard TSP is just a further constrained version of the shortest path problem.</p>\n\n<p>Specifically, I have the problem:</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Given a universe $\\mathcal{U}$ and a family $\\mathcal{S}$ of subsets of $\\mathcal{U}$, Select $k$ sets from $\\mathcal{S}$  such that the sum of the number of repeated times that each element is covered is maximized.\n  Number of repeats are defined as one less than the number of instances.</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>If the number of repeated times for each element has an upper bound at 2, this is equivalent the densest k-subgraph problem (edges are elements and nodes are sets),</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Given a graph $G$ and an integer $k$, find a subgraph of $G$ on $k$ nodes with maximum number of edges.</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>Since the densest k-subgraph problem is strongly NP Hard, can I prove that my problem is also NP Hard?</p>",

link) :</p>\n\n<p>I post the corrected ECM for the forum :</p>\n\n<pre><code>            \\documentclass[10pt]{article}\n\n                        \\usepackage{pgfplots}\n                        \\usepackage{subcaption}\n                        \\pgfplotsset{compat=1.10}\n\n                        \\begin{document}\n\n\n            \\begin{figure}[p]\n            \\centering\n                \\begin{tikzpicture}\n                    \\tikzstyle{every node}=[font=\\small]\n                    \\begin{axis}[height=0.8\\textwidth,width=0.8\\textwidth,\n            xlabel={$x_1$},\n            ylabel={y},\n            color=black,\n            scale only axis,\n            xmin=0,xmax=10,\n            x axis line style={black},\n            xtick style={black},\n            xticklabel style={black},\n            xtick={0,2,4,6,8,10},\n            xticklabels={0,2,4,6,8,10},\n            ymin=0,ymax=10,\n            ytick={0,2,4,6,8,10},\n            yticklabels={0,2,4,6,8,10},\n            axis x line*=bottom,\n            axis y line*=left,    \n            tick align = outside]\n            \\addplot[draw=black,mark=o,line width=1.5pt] 		"Title" : "There are TWO Settings that are independent of each other: Auto-Correct ...",
		"Body" : "<p>There are <strong>TWO Settings</strong> that are independent of each other: <strong>Auto-Correct</strong> and <strong>Spell-Check</strong>.  \"Auto-Correct\" can inadvertently change what you intended to write, while \"Spell-Check\" just independently and automatically marks misspellings.</p>\n\n<p>To change <strong>AUTO-CORRECT:</strong><br>\n-- Go to <strong>Settings...  Preferences...</strong><br>\n-- Then, on the left pane, under the \"Backup\" section, go to \n<strong>\"AUTO-COMPLETION\" section:</strong><br>\n-- Simply <strong>UN-check</strong> this choice.  (No NPP++ restart required)<br>\nThis does not turn off spell checking, so you will still see misspelled words marked with a red underline.  </p>\n\n<p>To change <strong>SPELL-CHECK:</strong><br>\nSimply toggle the <img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/Eke1H.jpg\" alt=\"Button with ABC and a ~~~ as an underline, on the toolbar\">, (or the DS button in older versions.) <strong>NOTE: This will NOT change the \"Auto-Completion\" setting.</strong></p>\n\n<p>No, you are not alone.... This \"Auto-Correct\" problem really \"bugged\" me until today.</p>\n\n<p>In the January 2015 version 6.7.4, by default, \"Spell-Checking\" now does a lot more than just \"check\" spelling.   Auto-Correct has been driving me mad, occasionally fixing my \"spelling\" for things like precise links that now no longer work, which I didn't notice were changed, until they failed.  </p>\n\n<p>NP++ Devs:  Thanks for all your work, but I'd suggest putting an on/off on the toolbar for both Auto-Correct and Spell-Check, and I'd suggest that you turn Auto-Check off by default.  Also, in preferences, call it \"spell-checking\" so we can find it, and allow me to change both settings under one place.  If that means that there are two places in the UI or prefs, then allow me to change both settings, both places, where it is obvious there are two separate settings.  </p>",

Is there some way to calculate this problem to get around this roadblock or am I approaching the problem incorrectly?</p>\n\n<p>I've tried applying the regular EOQ formula, that is q* = (2KD/h)^1/2 , where Demand is the 8500 value, but I ended up with a seemingly unusual value (which may be completely correct given my lack of experience in this field) : I received an answer close to 27,142 and using q/D to find the time gap between orders I arrived upon roughly 0.3 orders per month.</p>\n\n<p>I came here to ask two things: Is there a way to solve the former continuous model question? 	{
		"ReportLink" : "http://chat.meta.stackexchange.com/transcript/message/2922759",
		"PostUrl" : "http://linguistics.stackexchange.com/a/8607",
		"Site" : "linguistics.stackexchange.com",
		"Title" : "I do not have the linguistic competence of the users who commented the\nq...",
		"Body" : "<p>I do not have the linguistic competence of the users who commented the\nquestion. So I only took the question as asked, and looked also at\n<a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ergative_verb\" rel=\"nofollow\">wikipedia</a>,</p>\n\n<p>And the concept, as presented, looks very arbitrary to me.</p>\n\n<p>Here are examples involving the verbs <em>open</em> and <em>float</em>.</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>1.a: The door opened,</p>\n  \n  <p>1.b: He opened the door to a small garden,</p>\n  \n  <p>2.a: The trunk floated,</p>\n  \n  <p>2.b: He floated the trunks down the river,</p>\n  \n  <p>2.c: The man floated near his capsized boat.</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>According to the analysis of a previous question, case 1.a is an\nergative use of the verb <em>open</em>, used transitively in 1.b. But then\nthe sentences 2.a and 2.b should be analyzed in the same way, which\nimplies that 2.a is an ergative use of the verb <em>float</em>. But then,\nsentence 2.c should also be ergative. Is that the case?</p>\n\n<p>And then, in successive variations, what of:</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>The man stood near his boat</p>\n  \n  <p>The man walked near his boat</p>\n  \n  <p>The dog walked near his boat</p>\n  \n  <p>The man walked his dog near his boat</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p><strong>About question 1</strong>:</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ergative_verb\" rel=\"nofollow\">Wikipedia</a>'s answer is:</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>In linguistics, an ergative verb is a verb that can be either\n    transitive or intransitive, and whose subject when intransitive\n    corresponds to its direct object when transitive.</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>This seems to be illustrated by the question examples. But if you look\nat the second example:</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>He fired a gun. </p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>You can also say:</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>The gun fired a bullet.</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>and that is transitive.</p>\n\n<p>But what if the verb <em>shoot</em> is used.</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>He shot the gun</p>\n  \n  <p>He shot a man</p>\n  \n  <p>The gun shot a bullet</p>\n  \n  <p>The gun shot a man</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>Though I am not sure one would say intransitively</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>The gun shot</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>So it all seems a bit more complicated that the simple rule of\nWikipedia and your first question,</p>",

		"Title" : "How to implement error handling/returning while streaming a message",
		"Body" : "<p>Say someone calls a web service on a server, the relevant data is being retrieved in batches and the message is being streamed to the client. In the middle of the message some kind of exception is encountered. My current implementation sort of just stops streaming the (in this case soap) message and starts building an error message, but obviously the result won't be a valid message or even valid XML.</p>\n\n<p>I considered a few options, none of them seem to make much sense:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Put all the relevant data in memory and then only stream the message itself.</li>\n<li>Do a double-take, so see if it works out with a fake stream and then do the real stream.</li>\n<li>Stream to a disk first and then use a file input stream to stream to the client</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>As you can see all have serious downsides in terms of memory/disk consumption, speed/resource efficiency or even validity of the data. How would I best implement error handling in this situation? Do I just have to pick the least worst of these options? If so I tend to favor to the current situation where the message is just invalid in cases like these, because it at least doesn't affect the base case where everything is fine.</p>",
